# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: middle-ages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:middle-ages/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Initially influenced by Toulouse-Lautrec, Gauguin, and other late-19th-century innovators, Pablo Picasso made his first cubist paintings based on Cézanne's idea that all depiction of nature can be reduced to three solids: cube, sphere, and cone.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With the painting *Les Demoiselles d'Avignon* (1907; see gallery) Picasso created a new and radical picture depicting a raw and primitive brothel scene with five prostitutes, violently painted women, reminiscent of African tribal masks and his own new proto-Cubist inventions.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism, exemplified by *Violin and Candlestick, Paris*, was jointly developed by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque from about 1908 through 1912.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism was followed by Synthetic cubism, characterized by the introduction of different textures, surfaces, collage elements, papier collé and a large variety of merged subject matter.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the years between 1910 and the end of World War I and after the heyday of cubism, several movements emerged in Paris.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Giorgio de Chirico moved to Paris in July 1911, where he joined his brother Andrea (the poet and painter known as Alberto Savinio).
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Through his brother he met Pierre Laprade, a member of the jury at the Salon d'Automne, where he exhibited three of his dreamlike works: *Enigma of the Oracle*, *Enigma of an Afternoon* and *Self-Portrait*.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During 1913 he exhibited his work at the Salon des Indépendants and Salon d’Automne, where his work was noticed by Pablo Picasso, Guillaume Apollinaire, and others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His compelling and mysterious paintings are considered instrumental to the early beginnings of Surrealism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Song of Love* (1914) is one of the most famous works by de Chirico and is an early example of the surrealist style, though it was painted ten years before the movement was "founded" by André Breton in 1924.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Modern painting influenced all the visual arts, from Modernist architecture and design, to avant-garde film, theatre and modern dance, and became an experimental laboratory for the expression of visual experience, from photography and concrete poetry to advertising art and fashion.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Van Gogh's paintings exerted great influence upon 20th-century Expressionism, as can be seen in the work of the Fauves, Die Brücke (a group led by German painter Ernst Kirchner), and the Expressionism of Edvard Munch, Egon Schiele, Marc Chagall, Amedeo Modigliani, Chaïm Soutine, and others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Wassily Kandinsky, a Russian painter, printmaker and art theorist, is generally considered the first important painter of modern abstract art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As an early modernist, in search of new modes of visual expression, and spiritual expression, he theorized—as did contemporary occultists and theosophists—that pure visual abstraction had corollary vibrations with sound and music.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] They posited that pure abstraction could express pure spirituality.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His earliest abstractions were generally titled (as the example in the above gallery) *Composition VII*, making connection to the work of the composers of music.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kandinsky included many of his theories about abstract art in his book *Concerning the Spiritual in Art*.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Piet Mondrian's art was also related to his spiritual and philosophical studies.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1908 he became interested in the theosophical movement launched by Helena Petrovna Blavatsky in the late 19th century.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Blavatsky believed that it was possible to attain a knowledge of nature more profound than that provided by empirical means, and much of Mondrian's work for the rest of his life was inspired by his search for that spiritual knowledge.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other major pioneers of early abstraction include Swedish painter Hilma af Klint, Russian painter Kazimir Malevich, and Swiss painter Paul Klee.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Robert Delaunay was a French artist who is associated with Orphism, (reminiscent of a link between pure abstraction and cubism).
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His later works were more abstract, reminiscent of Paul Klee.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His key contributions to abstract painting refer to his bold use of color, and a clear love of experimentation of both depth and tone.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] At the invitation of Kandinsky, Delaunay and his wife the artist Sonia Delaunay, joined The Blue Rider (Der Blaue Reiter), a Munich-based group of abstract artists, in 1911, and his art took a turn to the abstract.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Still other important pioneers of abstract painting include Czech painter, František Kupka as well as American artists Stanton Macdonald-Wright and Morgan Russell who, in 1912, founded Synchromism, an art movement that closely resembles Orphism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Les Fauves (French for *The Wild Beasts*) were early-20th-century painters, experimenting with freedom of expression through color.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name was given, humorously and not as a compliment, to the group by art critic Louis Vauxcelles.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism was a short-lived and loose grouping of artists whose works emphasized painterly qualities and the imaginative use of deep color over the representational values.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvists made the subject of the painting easy to read and exaggerated perspectives.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The leaders of the movement were Henri Matisse and André Derain—friendly rivals of a sort, each with his own followers.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ultimately Matisse became the *yang* to Picasso's *yin* in the 20th century.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvist painters included Albert Marquet, Charles Camoin, Maurice de Vlaminck, Raoul Dufy, Othon Friesz, the Dutch painter Kees van Dongen, and Picasso's partner in Cubism, Georges Braque amongst others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism, as a movement, had no concrete theories, and was short lived, beginning in 1905 and ending in 1907.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse was seen as the leader of the movement, due to his seniority in age and prior self-establishment in the academic art world.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse, *The Green Line* (above), caused a sensation in Paris when it was first exhibited.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He said he wanted to create art to delight; art as a decoration was his purpose and it can be said that his use of bright colors tries to maintain serenity of composition.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1906 at the suggestion of his dealer Ambroise Vollard, André Derain went to London and produced a series of paintings like *Charing Cross Bridge, London* (above) in the Fauvist style, paraphrasing the famous series by the Impressionist painter Claude Monet.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] By 1907 Fauvism no longer was a shocking new movement, soon it was replaced by Cubism on the critics radar screen as the latest new development in Contemporary Art of the time.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter was a German movement lasting from 1911 to 1914, fundamental to Expressionism, along with Die Brücke, a group of German expressionist artists formed in Dresden in 1905.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Founding members of Die Brücke were Fritz Bleyl, Erich Heckel, Ernst Ludwig Kirchner and Karl Schmidt-Rottluff.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Later members included Max Pechstein, Otto Mueller and others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This was a seminal group, which in due course had a major impact on the evolution of modern art in the 20th century and created the style of Expressionism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter lacked a central artistic manifesto, but was centered around Kandinsky and Marc.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists Gabriele Münter and Paul Klee were also involved.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name of the movement comes from a painting by Kandinsky created in 1903.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is also claimed that the name could have derived from Marc's enthusiasm for horses and Kandinsky's love of the colour blue.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] For Kandinsky, *blue* is the colour of spirituality: the darker the blue, the more it awakens human desire for the eternal.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Marcel Duchamp came to international prominence in the wake of the New York City Armory Show in 1913 where his *Nude Descending a Staircase* became the *cause célèbre*.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He subsequently created *The Bride Stripped Bare by Her Bachelors, Even, Large Glass*.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Large Glass* pushed the art of painting to radical new limits being part painting, part collage, part construction.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp (who was soon to renounce artmaking for chess) became closely associated with the Dada movement that began in neutral Zürich, Switzerland, during World War I and peaked from 1916 to 1920.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The movement primarily involved visual arts, literature (poetry, art manifestoes, art theory), theatre, and graphic design, and concentrated its anti war politic through a rejection of the prevailing standards in art through anti-art cultural works.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Francis Picabia, Man Ray, Kurt Schwitters, Tristan Tzara, Hans Richter, Jean Arp, Sophie Taeuber-Arp, along with Duchamp and many others are associated with the Dadaist movement.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp and several Dadaists are also associated with Surrealism, the movement that dominated European painting in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1924 André Breton published the *Surrealist Manifesto.* The Surrealist movement in painting became synonymous with the avant-garde and which featured artists whose works varied from the abstract to the super-realist.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With works on paper like *Machine Turn Quickly* (above) Francis Picabia continued his involvement in the Dada movement through 1919 in Zürich and Paris, before breaking away from it after developing an interest in Surrealist art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Yves Tanguy, René Magritte and Salvador Dalí are particularly known for their realistic depictions of dream imagery and fantastic manifestations of the imagination.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Joan Miró's *The Tilled Field* of 1923–1924 verges on abstraction, this early painting of a complex of objects and figures, and arrangements of sexually active characters; was Miró's first Surrealist masterpiece.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The more abstract Joan Miró, Jean Arp, André Masson, and Max Ernst were very influential, especially in the United States during the 1940s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 1930s, Surrealism continued to become more visible to the public at large.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] A Surrealist group developed in Britain and, according to Breton, their 1936 London International Surrealist Exhibition was a high-water mark of the period and became the model for international exhibitions.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Surrealist groups in Japan, and especially in Latin America, the Caribbean and in Mexico produced innovative and original works.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí and Magritte created some of the most widely recognized images of the movement.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1928/1929 painting *This Is Not A Pipe* by Magritte is the subject of a Michel Foucault 1973 book, *This is not a Pipe* (English edition, 1991), that discusses the painting and its paradox.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí joined the group in 1929, and participated in the rapid establishment of the visual style between 1930 and 1935.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Evocations of time and its compelling mystery and absurdity.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Max Ernst studied philosophy and psychology in Bonn and was interested in the alternative realities experienced by the insane.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His paintings, such as *Murdering Airplane* (1920), may have been inspired by the psychoanalyst Sigmund Freud's study of the delusions of a paranoiac, Daniel Paul Schreber.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Freud identified Schreber's fantasy of becoming a woman as a *castration complex*.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The central image of two pairs of legs refers to Schreber's hermaphroditic desires.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ernst's inscription on the back of the painting reads: *The picture is curious because of its symmetry.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s André Masson's work was enormously influential in helping the young artist Joan Miró find his roots in the new Surrealist painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Miró acknowledged in letters to his dealer Pierre Matisse the importance of Masson as an example to him in his early years in Paris.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Long after personal, political and professional tensions have fragmented the Surrealist group into thin air and ether, Magritte, Miró, Dalí and the other Surrealists continue to define a visual program in the arts.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other prominent surrealist artists include Giorgio de Chirico, Méret Oppenheim, Toyen, Grégoire Michonze, Roberto Matta, Kay Sage, Leonora Carrington, Dorothea Tanning, and Leonor Fini among others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s and the 1930s and the Great Depression, the European art scene was characterized by Surrealism, late Cubism, the Bauhaus, De Stijl, Dada, Neue Sachlichkeit, and Expressionism; and was occupied by masterful modernist color painters like Henri Matisse and Pierre Bonnard.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Scene painting and the Social Realism and Regionalism movements that contained both political and social commentary dominated the art world in the USA.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, Grant Wood, George Tooker, John Steuart Curry, Reginald Marsh, and others became prominent.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo's Symbolist works also relate strongly to Surrealism and to the Magic Realism movement in literature.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The psychological drama in many of Kahlo's self-portraits (above) underscore the vitality and relevance of her paintings to artists in the 21st century.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Germany Neue Sachlichkeit ("New Objectivity") emerged as Max Beckmann, Otto Dix, George Grosz and others associated with the Berlin Secession politicized their paintings.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The work of these artists grew out of expressionism, and was a response to the political tensions of the Weimar Republic, and was often sharply satirical.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Diego Rivera is perhaps best known by the public for his 1933 mural, *Man at the Crossroads*, in the lobby of the RCA Building at Rockefeller Center.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] When his patron Nelson Rockefeller discovered that the mural included a portrait of Lenin and other communist imagery, he fired Rivera, and the unfinished work was eventually destroyed by Rockefeller's staff.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The film *Cradle Will Rock* includes a dramatization of the controversy.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo (Rivera's wife's) works are often characterized by their stark portrayals of pain.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Of her 143 paintings 55 are self-portraits, which frequently incorporate symbolic portrayals of her physical and psychological wounds.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kahlo was deeply influenced by indigenous Mexican culture, which is apparent in her paintings' bright colors and dramatic symbolism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Christian and Jewish themes are often depicted in her work as well; she combined elements of the classic religious Mexican tradition—which were often bloody and violent—with surrealist renderings.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] While her paintings are not overtly Christian—she was an avowed communist—they certainly contain elements of the macabre Mexican Christian style of religious paintings.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s radical leftist politics characterized many of the artists connected to Surrealism, including Pablo Picasso.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] On 26 April 1937, during the Spanish Civil War, the Basque town of Gernika was the scene of the "Bombing of Gernika" by the Condor Legion of Nazi Germany's Luftwaffe.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The Germans were attacking to support the efforts of Francisco Franco to overthrow the Basque Government and the Spanish Republican government.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The town was devastated, though the Biscayan assembly and the Oak of Gernika survived.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted his mural sized *Guernica* to commemorate the horrors of the bombing.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In its final form, *Guernica* is an immense black and white, 3.5 metre (11 ft) tall and 7.8 metre (23 ft) wide mural painted in oil.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The mural presents a scene of death, violence, brutality, suffering, and helplessness without portraying their immediate causes.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The choice to paint in black and white contrasts with the intensity of the scene depicted and invokes the immediacy of a newspaper photograph.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted the mural sized painting called *Guernica* in protest of the bombing.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting was first exhibited in Paris in 1937, then Scandinavia, then London in 1938 and finally in 1939 at Picasso's request the painting was sent to the United States in an extended loan (for safekeeping) at MoMA.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting went on a tour of museums throughout the U.S. until its final return to the Museum of Modern Art in New York City where it was exhibited for nearly thirty years.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Finally in accord with Picasso's wish to give the painting to the people of Spain as a gift, it was sent to Spain in 1981.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the Great Depression of the 1930s, through the years of World War II American art was characterized by Social Realism and American Scene Painting (as seen above) in the work of Grant Wood, Edward Hopper, Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, and several others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Nighthawks* (1942) is a painting by Edward Hopper that portrays people sitting in a downtown diner late at night.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is not only Hopper's most famous painting, but one of the most recognizable in American art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is currently in the collection of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The scene was inspired by a diner (since demolished) in Greenwich Village, Hopper's home neighborhood in Manhattan.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Hopper began painting it immediately after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After this event there was a large feeling of gloominess over the country, a feeling that is portrayed in the painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The urban street is empty outside the diner, and inside none of the three patrons is apparently looking or talking to the others but instead is lost in their own thoughts.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This portrayal of modern urban life as empty or lonely is a common theme throughout Hopper's work.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1940s in New York City heralded the triumph of American abstract expressionism, a modernist movement that combined lessons learned from Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Surrealism, Joan Miró, Cubism, Fauvism, and early Modernism via great teachers in America like Hans Hofmann and John D.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American artists benefited from the presence of Piet Mondrian, Fernand Léger, Max Ernst and the André Breton group, Pierre Matisse's gallery, and Peggy Guggenheim's The Art of This Century Gallery, as well as other factors.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Abstract Expressionism got its name in 1946 from the art critic Robert Coates.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is seen as combining the emotional intensity and self-denial of the German Expressionists with the anti-figurative aesthetic of the European abstract schools such as Futurism, the Bauhaus and Synthetic Cubism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract Expressionism, Action painting, and Color Field painting are synonymous with the New York School.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Technically Surrealism was an important predecessor for Abstract expressionism with its emphasis on spontaneous, automatic or subconscious creation.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Jackson Pollock's dripping paint onto a canvas laid on the floor is a technique that has its roots in the work of André Masson.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Another important early manifestation of what came to be abstract expressionism is the work of American Northwest artist Mark Tobey, especially his "white writing" canvases, which, though generally not large in scale, anticipate the "all over" look of Pollock's drip paintings.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Additionally, abstract expressionism has an image of being rebellious, anarchic, highly idiosyncratic and, some feel, rather nihilistic.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In practice, the term is applied to any number of artists working (mostly) in New York who had quite different styles, and even applied to work which is not especially abstract nor expressionist.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Pollock's energetic "action paintings", with their "busy" feel, are different both technically and aesthetically, to the violent and grotesque *Women* series of Willem de Kooning.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As seen above in the gallery *Woman V* is one of a series of six paintings made by de Kooning between 1950 and 1953 that depict a three-quarter-length female figure.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He began the first of these paintings, *Woman I* collection: The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, in June 1950, repeatedly changing and painting out the image until January or February 1952, when the painting was abandoned unfinished.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The art historian Meyer Schapiro saw the painting in de Kooning's studio soon afterwards and encouraged the artist to persist.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Kooning's response was to begin three other paintings on the same theme; *Woman II*, The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, *Woman III*, Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art, *Woman IV*, Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the summer of 1952, spent at East Hampton, de Kooning further explored the theme through drawings and pastels.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He may have finished work on *Woman I* by the end of June, or possibly as late as November 1952, and probably the other three women pictures were concluded at much the same time.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Woman series* are decidedly figurative paintings.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Both Hans Hofmann and Robert Motherwell (gallery) can be comfortably described as practitioners of action painting and Color field painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism has many stylistic similarities to the Russian artists of the early twentieth century such as Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although it is true that spontaneity or of the impression of spontaneity characterized many of the abstract expressionists works, most of these paintings involved careful planning, especially since their large size demanded it.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] An exception might be the drip paintings of Pollock.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Why this style gained mainstream acceptance in the 1950s is a matter of debate.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Social realism had been the mainstream in the 1930s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It had been influenced not only by the Great Depression but also by the Social Realists of Mexico such as David Alfaro Siqueiros and Diego Rivera.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The political climate after World War II did not long tolerate the social protests of those painters.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism arose during World War II and began to be showcased during the early 1940s at galleries in New York like The Art of This Century Gallery.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The late 1940s through the mid-1950s ushered in the McCarthy era.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It was after World War II and a time of political conservatism and extreme artistic censorship in the United States.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Some people have conjectured that since the subject matter was often totally abstract, Abstract expressionism became a safe strategy for artists to pursue this style.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract art could be seen as apolitical.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Or if the art was political, the message was largely for the insiders.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] However those theorists are in the minority.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As the first truly original school of painting in America, Abstract expressionism demonstrated the vitality and creativity of the country in the post-war years, as well as its ability (or need) to develop an aesthetic sense that was not constrained by the European standards of beauty.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although Abstract expressionism spread quickly throughout the United States, the major centers of this style were New York City and California, especially in the New York School, and the San Francisco Bay area.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionist paintings share certain characteristics, including the use of large canvases, an "all-over" approach, in which the whole canvas is treated with equal importance (as opposed to the center being of more interest than the edges).
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The canvas as the *arena* became a credo of Action painting, while the *integrity of the picture plane* became a credo of the Color Field painters.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1950s, Color Field painting initially referred to a particular type of abstract expressionism, especially the work of Mark Rothko, Clyfford Still, Barnett Newman, Robert Motherwell and Adolph Gottlieb.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It essentially involved abstract paintings with large, flat expanses of color that expressed the sensual, and visual feelings and properties of large areas of nuanced surface.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Art critic Clement Greenberg perceived Color Field painting as related to but different from Action painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The overall expanse and gestalt of the work of the early color field painters speaks of an almost religious experience, awestruck in the face of an expanding universe of sensuality, color and surface.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Clyfford Still, Mark Rothko, Hans Hofmann, Morris Louis, Jules Olitski, Kenneth Noland, Helen Frankenthaler, Larry Zox, and others often used greatly reduced references to nature, and they painted with a highly articulated and psychological use of color.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In general these artists eliminated recognizable imagery.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In *Mountains and Sea,* from 1952, a seminal work of Colorfield painting by Helen Frankenthaler the artist used the stain technique for the first time.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Europe there was the continuation of Surrealism, Cubism, Dada and the works of Matisse.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Also in Europe, Tachisme (the European equivalent to Abstract expressionism) and Informalism took hold of the newest generation.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Serge Poliakoff, Nicolas de Staël, Georges Mathieu, Vieira da Silva, Jean Dubuffet, Yves Klein and Pierre Soulages among others are considered important figures in post-war European painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Eventually abstract painting in America evolved into movements such as Neo-Dada, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, Neo-expressionism and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As a response to the tendency toward abstraction imagery emerged through various new movements, notably Pop art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s through the 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Abstract Expressionism, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, and Lyrical abstraction.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other artists reacted as a response to the tendency toward abstraction allowing imagery to continue through various new contexts like the Bay Area Figurative Movement in the 1950s and new forms of expressionism from the 1940s through the 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Italy during this time, Giorgio Morandi was the foremost still life painter, exploring a wide variety of approaches to depicting everyday bottles and kitchen implements.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 20th century many painters practiced Realism and used expressive imagery; practicing landscape and figurative painting with contemporary subjects and solid technique, and unique expressivity like Milton Avery, John D.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham, Fairfield Porter, Edward Hopper, Andrew Wyeth, Balthus, Francis Bacon, Frank Auerbach, Lucian Freud, Leon Kossoff, Philip Pearlstein, Willem de Kooning, Arshile Gorky, Grace Hartigan, Robert De Niro, Sr., Elaine de Kooning and others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Pierre Bonnard, Georges Braque, and other 20th-century masters.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The figurative work of Francis Bacon, Frida Kahlo, Edward Hopper, Lucian Freud Andrew Wyeth and others served as a kind of alternative to abstract expressionism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] One of the most well-known images in 20th-century American art is Wyeth's painting, *Christina's World*, currently in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York City.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It depicts a woman lying on the ground in a treeless, mostly tawny field, looking up at and crawling towards a gray house on the horizon; a barn and various other small outbuildings are adjacent to the house.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This tempera work, done in a realist style, is nearly always on display at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Arshile Gorky's portrait of what may be his friend Willem de Kooning (left) is an example of the evolution of Abstract Expressionism from the context of figure painting, cubism and surrealism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with his friends de Kooning and John D.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham Gorky created bio-morphically shaped and abstracted figurative compositions that by the 1940s evolved into totally abstract paintings.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Gorky's work seems to be a careful analysis of memory, emotion and shape, using line and color to express feeling and nature.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After World War II the term School of Paris often referred to Tachisme, the European equivalent of American Abstract expressionism and those artists are also related to Cobra.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1952 Michel Tapié authored the book *Un Autre art* which gave name and voice to Informalism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Important proponents being Jean Dubuffet, Pierre Soulages, Nicolas de Staël, Hans Hartung, Serge Poliakoff, and Georges Mathieu, among several others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the early 1950s Dubuffet (who was always a figurative artist), and de Staël, abandoned abstraction, and returned to imagery via figuration and landscape.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Staël 's work was quickly recognised within the post-war art world, and he became one of the most influential artists of the 1950s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Much of de Staël 's late work – in particular his thinned, and diluted oil on canvas abstract landscapes of the mid-1950s predicts Color Field painting and Lyrical Abstraction of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Nicolas de Staël's bold and intensely vivid color in his last paintings predict the direction of much of contemporary painting that came after him including Pop art of the 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art in America was to a large degree initially inspired by the works of Jasper Johns, Larry Rivers, and Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although the paintings of Gerald Murphy, Stuart Davis and Charles Demuth during the 1920s and 1930s set the table for Pop art in America.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In New York City during the mid-1950s Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns created works of art that at first seemed to be continuations of Abstract expressionist painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Actually their works and the work of Larry Rivers, were radical departures from abstract expressionism especially in the use of banal and literal imagery and the inclusion and the combining of mundane materials into their work.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Eventually by 1963 the movement came to be known worldwide as Pop art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art is exemplified by artists: Andy Warhol, Claes Oldenburg, Wayne Thiebaud, James Rosenquist, Jim Dine, Tom Wesselmann and Roy Lichtenstein among others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein used oil and Magna paint in his best known works, such as *Drowning Girl* (1963), which was appropriated from the lead story in DC Comics' *Secret Hearts* #83.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] (*Drowning Girl* now is in the collection of Museum of Modern Art, New York.) Also featuring thick outlines, bold colors and Ben-Day dots to represent certain colors, as if created by photographic reproduction.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein would say of his own work: Abstract Expressionists "put things down on the canvas and responded to what they had done, to the color positions and sizes.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In October 1962 the Sidney Janis Gallery mounted *The New Realists* the first major Pop art group exhibition in an uptown art gallery in New York City.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Sidney Janis mounted the exhibition in a 57th Street storefront near his gallery at 15 E.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The show sent shockwaves through the New York School and reverberated worldwide.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in the fall of 1962 a historically important and ground-breaking *New Painting of Common Objects* exhibition of Pop art, curated by Walter Hopps at the Pasadena Art Museum sent shock waves across the Western United States.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Campbell's Soup Cans* (sometimes referred to as *32 Campbell's Soup Cans*) is the title of an Andy Warhol work of art that was produced in 1962.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It consists of thirty-two canvases, each measuring 20 inches in height x 16 inches in width (50.8 x 40.6 cm) and each consisting of a painting of a Campbell's Soup can—one of each canned soup variety the company offered at the time.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The individual paintings were produced with a semi-mechanised silkscreen process, using a non-painterly style.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] They helped usher in Pop art as a major art movement that relied on themes from popular culture.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works by Andy Warhol are repetitive and they are made in a non-painterly commercial manner.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in England in 1956 the term *Pop Art* was used by Lawrence Alloway for paintings that celebrated consumerism of the post World War II era.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement rejected Abstract expressionism and its focus on the hermeneutic and psychological interior, in favor of art which depicted, and often celebrated material consumer culture, advertising, and iconography of the mass production age.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The early works of David Hockney whose paintings emerged from England during the 1960s like *A Bigger Splash,* and the works of Richard Hamilton, Peter Blake, and Eduardo Paolozzi, are considered seminal examples in the movement.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in the downtown scene in New York's East Village 10th Street galleries artists were formulating an American version of Pop art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Claes Oldenburg had his storefront, and the Green Gallery on 57th Street began to show Tom Wesselmann and James Rosenquist.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later Leo Castelli exhibited other American artists including the bulk of the careers of Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein and his use of Benday dots, a technique used in commercial reproduction and seen in ordinary comic books and in paintings like *Drowning Girl*, 1963, in the gallery above.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] There is a connection between the radical works of Duchamp, and Man Ray, the rebellious Dadaists – with a sense of humor; and Pop Artists like Alex Katz (who became known for his parodies of portrait photography and suburban life), Claes Oldenburg, Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein and the others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] 1),* 1963, Oil on canvas, 60 1/4 x 50 1/2 inches, collection: San Francisco Museum of Modern Art), and later in the 1970s Neo-expressionism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bay Area Figurative Movement of whom David Park, Elmer Bischoff, Nathan Oliveira and Richard Diebenkorn whose painting *Cityscape 1,* 1963 is a typical example were influential members flourished during the 1950s and 1960s in California.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Younger painters practiced the use of imagery in new and radical ways.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Yves Klein, Martial Raysse, Niki de Saint Phalle, David Hockney, Alex Katz, Antoni Tàpies, Malcolm Morley, Ralph Goings, Audrey Flack, Richard Estes, Chuck Close, Susan Rothenberg, Eric Fischl, John Baeder, and Vija Celmins were a few who became prominent between the 1960s and the 1980s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fairfield Porter was largely self-taught, and produced representational work in the midst of the Abstract Expressionist movement.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His subjects were primarily landscapes, domestic interiors and portraits of family, friends and fellow artists, many of them affiliated with the New York School of writers, including John Ashbery, Frank O'Hara, and James Schuyler.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many of his paintings were set in or around the family summer house on Great Spruce Head Island, Maine.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-Dada is a movement that started in the 1950s and 1960s and was related to Abstract expressionism only with imagery.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Featuring the emergence of combined manufactured items, with artist materials, moving away from previous conventions of painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This trend in art is exemplified by the work of Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg, whose "combines" in the 1950s were forerunners of Pop Art and Installation art, and made use of the assemblage of large physical objects, including stuffed animals, birds and commercial photography.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s and 1970s abstract painting continued to develop in America through varied styles.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Geometric abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Color Field painting and minimal painting, were some interrelated directions for advanced abstract painting as well as some other new movements.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Morris Louis was an important pioneer in advanced Colorfield painting, his work can serve as a bridge between Abstract expressionism, Colorfield painting, and Minimal Art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Two influential teachers Josef Albers and Hans Hofmann introduced a new generation of American artists to their advanced theories of color and space.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Josef Albers is best remembered for his work as a Geometric abstractionist painter and theorist.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Most famous are the hundreds of paintings and prints that make up the series *Homage to the Square*.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this rigorous series, begun in 1949, Albers explored chromatic interactions with flat colored squares arranged concentrically on the canvas.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Albers' theories on art and education were formative for the next generation of artists.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His own paintings form the foundation of both hard-edge painting and Op art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many Geometric abstract artists, minimalists, and Hard-edge painters elected to use the edges of the image to define the shape of the painting rather than accepting the rectangular format.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In fact, the use of the shaped canvas is primarily associated with paintings of the 1960s and 1970s that are coolly abstract, formalistic, geometrical, objective, rationalistic, clean-lined, brashly sharp-edged, or minimalist in character.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bykert Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Minimalism and shaped canvas painting in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In 1965, an exhibition called *The Responsive Eye*, curated by William C.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Seitz, was held at the Museum of Modern Art, in New York City.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The works shown were wide-ranging, encompassing the Minimalism of Frank Stella, the Op art of Larry Poons, the work of Alexander Liberman, alongside the masters of the Op Art movement: Victor Vasarely, Richard Anuszkiewicz, Bridget Riley and others.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The exhibition focused on the perceptual aspects of art, which result both from the illusion of movement and the interaction of color relationships.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art, also known as optical art, is a style present in some paintings and other works of art that use optical illusions.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is also closely akin to geometric abstraction and hard-edge painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although sometimes the term used for it is perceptual abstraction.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is a method of painting concerning the interaction between illusion and picture plane, between understanding and seeing.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art works are abstract, with many of the better known pieces made in only black and white.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] When the viewer looks at them, the impression is given of movement, hidden images, flashing and vibration, patterns, or alternatively, of swelling or warping.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting clearly pointed toward a new direction in American painting, away from abstract expressionism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting is related to Post-painterly abstraction, Suprematism, Abstract Expressionism, Hard-edge painting and Lyrical Abstraction.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting sought to rid art of superfluous rhetoric.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Certain artists made references to past or present art, but in general color field painting presents abstraction as an end in itself.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In pursuing this direction of modern art, artists wanted to present each painting as one unified, cohesive, monolithic image.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Frank Stella, Kenneth Noland, Ellsworth Kelly, Barnett Newman, Ronald Davis, Neil Williams, Robert Mangold, Charles Hinman, Richard Tuttle, David Novros, and Alvin Loving are examples of artists associated with the use of the shaped canvas during the period beginning in the early 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] From 1960 Frank Stella produced paintings in aluminium and copper paint and are his first works using shaped canvases (canvases in a shape other than the traditional rectangle or square), often being in L, N, U or T-shapes.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These later developed into more elaborate designs, in the *Irregular Polygon* series (67), for example.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Also in the 1960s, Stella began to use a wider range of colors, typically arranged in straight or curved lines.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later he began his *Protractor Series* (71) of paintings, in which arcs, sometimes overlapping, within square borders are arranged side-by-side to produce full and half circles painted in rings of concentric color.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Harran II,* 1967, is an example of the *Protractor Series*.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These paintings are named after circular cities he had visited while in the Middle East earlier in the 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Irregular Polygon canvases and Protractor series further extended the concept of the shaped canvas.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Andre Emmerich Gallery, the Leo Castelli Gallery, the Richard Feigen Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Color Field painting, shaped canvas painting and Lyrical Abstraction in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s Color Field painting and Minimal art were often closely associated with each other.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In actuality by the early 1970s both movements became decidedly diverse.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Another related movement of the late 1960s, Lyrical Abstraction (the term being coined by Larry Aldrich, the founder of the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum, Ridgefield Connecticut), encompassed what Aldrich said he saw in the studios of many artists at that time.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It is also the name of an exhibition that originated in the Aldrich Museum and traveled to the Whitney Museum of American Art and other museums throughout the United States between 1969 and 1971.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Postminimalism often incorporating industrial materials, raw materials, fabrications, found objects, installation, serial repetition, and often with references to Dada and Surrealism is best exemplified in the sculptures of Eva Hesse.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction is a type of freewheeling abstract painting that emerged in the mid-1960s when abstract painters returned to various forms of painterly, pictorial, expressionism with a predominate focus on process, gestalt and repetitive compositional strategies in general.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction shares similarities with Color Field painting and Abstract Expressionism especially in the freewheeling usage of paint – texture and surface.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Direct drawing, calligraphic use of line, the effects of brushed, splattered, stained, squeegeed, poured, and splashed paint superficially resemble the effects seen in Abstract Expressionism and Color Field painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] However the styles are markedly different.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Setting it apart from Abstract Expressionism and Action Painting of the 1940s and 1950s is the approach to composition and drama.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] As seen in Action Painting there is an emphasis on brushstrokes, high compositional drama, dynamic compositional tension.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in Lyrical Abstraction as exemplified by the 1971 Ronnie Landfield painting *Garden of Delight* (above), there is a sense of compositional randomness, all over composition, low key and relaxed compositional drama and an emphasis on process, repetition, and an all over sensibility.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Donald Judd had started as a painter, and ended as a creator of objects.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His seminal essay, "Specific Objects" (published in Arts Yearbook 8, 1965), was a touchstone of theory for the formation of Minimalist aesthetics.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this essay, Judd found a starting point for a new territory for American art, and a simultaneous rejection of residual inherited European artistic values.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He pointed to evidence of this development in the works of an array of artists active in New York at the time, including Jasper Johns, Dan Flavin and Lee Bontecou.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Of "preliminary" importance for Judd was the work of George Earl Ortman, who had concretized and distilled painting's forms into blunt, tough, philosophically charged geometries.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These Specific Objects inhabited a space not then comfortably classifiable as either painting or sculpture.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] That the categorical identity of such objects was itself in question, and that they avoided easy association with well-worn and over-familiar conventions, was a part of their value for Judd.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] American painters such as Brice Marden and Cy Twombly show a clear European influence in their *pure* abstraction, minimalist painting of the 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ronald Davis polyurethane works from the late 1960s pay homage to the *Broken Glass* of Marcel Duchamp.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement was heavily criticised by high modernist formalist art critics and historians.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some anxious critics thought Minimalist art represented a misunderstanding of the modern dialectic of painting and sculpture as defined by critic Clement Greenberg, arguably the dominant American critic of painting in the period leading up to the 1960s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The most notable critique of Minimalism was produced by Michael Fried, a Greenbergian critic, who objected to the work on the basis of its "theatricality".
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In *Art and Objecthood* (published in Artforum in June 1967) he declared that the Minimalist work of art, particularly Minimalist sculpture, was based on an engagement with the physicality of the spectator.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He argued that work like Robert Morris's transformed the act of viewing into a type of spectacle, in which the artifice of the act observation and the viewer's participation in the work were unveiled.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fried saw this displacement of the viewer's experience from an aesthetic engagement within, to an event outside of the artwork as a failure of Minimal art.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ad Reinhardt, actually an artist of the Abstract Expressionist generation, but one whose reductive all-black paintings seemed to anticipate minimalism, had this to say about the value of a reductive approach to art: "The more stuff in it, the busier the work of art, the worse it is.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Still other important innovations in abstract painting took place during the 1960s and the 1970s characterized by monochrome painting and hard-edge painting inspired by Ad Reinhardt, Barnett Newman, Milton Resnick, and Ellsworth Kelly.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Artists as diverse as Agnes Martin, Al Held, Larry Zox, Frank Stella, Larry Poons, Brice Marden and others explored the power of simplification.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The convergence of Color Field painting, minimal art, hard-edge painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and postminimalism blurred the distinction between movements that became more apparent in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The neo-expressionism movement is related to earlier developments in abstract expressionism, neo-Dada, Lyrical Abstraction and postminimal painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works were inspirational to a new generation of painters interested in a revival of expressive imagery.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His painting *Painting, Smoking, Eating* 1973, seen above in the gallery is an example of Guston's final and conclusive return to representation.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, there was also a return to painting that occurred almost simultaneously in Italy, Germany, France and Britain.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These movements were called Transavantguardia, Neue Wilde, Figuration Libre, Neo-expressionism, the school of London, and in the late 1990s the Stuckists, a group that emerged late in 1990s respectively.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These painting were characterized by large formats, free expressive mark making, figuration, myth and imagination.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] All work in this genre came to be labeled neo-expressionism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some critics regarded it as driven by profit motivations by large commercial galleries.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This type of art continues in popularity into the 21st century, even after the art crash of the late 1980s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the late 1970s in the United States painters who began working with invigorated surfaces and who returned to imagery like Susan Rothenberg gained in popularity, especially as seen above in paintings like *Horse 2,* 1979.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1980s American artists like Eric Fischl, David Salle, Jean-Michel Basquiat (who began as a graffiti artist), Julian Schnabel, and Keith Haring, and Italian painters like Mimmo Paladino, Sandro Chia, and Enzo Cucchi, among others defined the idea of Neo-expressionism in America.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionism was a style of modern painting that became popular in the late 1970s and dominated the art market until the mid-1980s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It developed in Europe as a reaction against the conceptual and minimalistic art of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionists returned to portraying recognizable objects, such as the human body (although sometimes in a virtually abstract manner), in a rough and violently emotional way using vivid colours and banal colour harmonies.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The veteran painters Philip Guston, Frank Auerbach, Leon Kossoff, Gerhard Richter, A.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Penck and Georg Baselitz, along with slightly younger artists like Anselm Kiefer, Eric Fischl, Susan Rothenberg, Francesco Clemente, Damien Hirst, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Julian Schnabel, Keith Haring, and many others became known for working in this intense expressionist vein of painting.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] At the beginning of the 21st century Contemporary painting and Contemporary art in general continues in several contiguous modes, characterized by the idea of pluralism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Mainstream painting has been rejected by artists of the postmodern era in favor of artistic pluralism.
[src:middle-ages/20th-century-western-painting-p02] According to art critic Arthur Danto there is an *anything goes* attitude that prevails; an "everything going on", and consequently "nothing going on" syndrome; this creates an aesthetic traffic jam with no firm and clear direction and with every lane on the artistic superhighway filled to capacity.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] The program started in 1947 as the "Plan to Effect Standardization" between the armies of the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada (the ABC Armies), with the three nations looking to capitalize on the close cooperation between the forces during World War II.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] In 1954, the Plan was replaced by the "Basic Standardization Concept".
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] Australia joined the organization in 1963, and the ABCA Program was established with the ratification of the "Basic Standardization Agreement 1964" on 1 October 1964.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] In 1965, Australia successfully sponsored the introduction of New Zealand to the agreement as an observer.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] Originally, the role of ABCANZ was limited to issues of standardization for soldier equipment, training, and tactics.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] Following the September 11 attacks, a review by the Program's Heads of Delegations saw the Program modified to address the changing security environment and improve responsiveness, relevance, and focus on interoperability.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] The overhaul was completed by June 2004.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] Also in 2004, the increasing involvement of the United States Marine Corps was formally recognized with a Memorandum of Understanding between the Corps and the United States Army, allowing both forces to be represented by a single position.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] Following this, the United Kingdom delegation successfully incorporated the Royal Marines.
[src:middle-ages/abcanz-armies] New Zealand became a full member of ABCA in early 2006.
[src:middle-ages/ad-711] Year **711** (**DCCXI**) was a common year starting on Thursday of the Julian calendar.
[src:middle-ages/ad-711] The denomination 711 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] The land component of ANZUK Force was the units of 28th Commonwealth Infantry Brigade Group renamed and relocated from Malaysia to Singapore.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] Sea and Air components did not wear any of the patches as they remained under national command and were only attached to NZUK command on an as required basis.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] By 1973 the political climate in Australia and the United Kingdom had changed and it was deemed that ANZUK should be disbanded.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] Rear Admiral Wells, the First ANZUK commander who established the Force, had the task of planning the run-down phase and handing over to his successor Air Vice Marshal Richard Gordon Wakeford, to follow through.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] Australia would be retaining a presence in Butterworth in Malaysia and the United Kingdom had decided to withdraw all its forces east of Suez.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] It was in New Zealand's interest to retain a force in southeast Asia, so on 30 January 1974 New Zealand Force South East Asia was formed, taking under its command all the New Zealand units formerly part of ANZUK.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] Over the course of 1974 the integrated units which made up the ANZUK were gradually disbanded and replaced by national units.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] On 31 January 1974 ceased to exist, followed on 16 December 1974 with the disbanding of the Naval and Air Headquarters and their assets reverted to their respective national command and what remained of the United Kingdom's land component forces became the 28th (UK) Infantry Brigade.
[src:middle-ages/anzuk] Taking several years for the Australian and United Kingdom units to draw down and withdraw, it was not until 1977 that NZFORSEA was the sole remaining foreign presence in Singapore.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The **Australia, New Zealand, United States Security Treaty** (**ANZUS** or **ANZUS Treaty**) is a collective security agreement between Australia, New Zealand, and the United States that was signed in 1951, and from which New Zealand has been partially suspended since 1986.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] It firstly recommits the parties to the purposes of the United Nations, prohibiting the use of force or threats except in self-defence.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] It also provides for a council of the signatories foreign ministers, in which the implementation of the treaty can be discussed.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The treaty was one of a series that the United States formed in the 1949–1955 era as part of its collective response to the threat of communism during the Cold War.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] New Zealand was suspended from ANZUS in 1986 as it initiated a nuclear-free zone in its territorial waters.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In late 2012, the United States lifted a 26-year-old ban on visits by New Zealand warships to US Department of Defense and US Coast Guard bases around the world.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The treaty was previously a full three-way defence pact, but was disrupted following a dispute between New Zealand and the United States in 1984 over visiting rights for ships and submarines capable of carrying nuclear arms or nuclear-powered ships of the US Navy to New Zealand ports.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The treaty has lapsed between the United States and New Zealand, but remains separately in force between both of those states and Australia.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In 2000, the United States opened its ports to the Royal New Zealand Navy once again, and under the presidency of Bill Clinton in the US and the government of Helen Clark in New Zealand, the countries have since reestablished bilateral cooperation on defence and security.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] While ANZUS is commonly recognised to have split in 1984, the Australia–US alliance remains in full force.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Heads of defence of one or both states often have joined the annual ministerial meetings, which are supplemented by consultations between the US Combatant Commander Pacific and the Australian Chief of Defence Force.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] There are also regular civilian and military consultations between the two governments at lower levels.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Annual meetings to discuss ANZUS defence matters take place between the United States Secretaries of Defense and State and the Australian Ministers of Defence and Foreign Affairs, and are known by the acronym AUSMIN.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Unlike the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), ANZUS has no integrated defence structure or dedicated forces.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Nevertheless, Australia and the United States conduct a variety of joint activities.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] These include military exercises ranging from naval and landing exercises at the task-group level to battalion-level special forces training, assigning officers to each other's armed services, and standardising equipment and operational doctrine.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The two countries also operate several joint-defence facilities in Australia, mainly ground stations for spy satellite, and signals intelligence espionage in Southeast and East Asia as part of the ECHELON network.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] During the 2010s, New Zealand and the US resumed a close relationship, although it is unclear whether the revived partnership falls under the aegis of the 1951 trilateral treaty.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The Wellington Declaration of 2010 defined a "strategic partnership" between New Zealand and the US, and New Zealand joined the biennial Rim of the Pacific military exercise off Hawaii in 2012, for the first time since 1984.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The US prohibition on New Zealand ships making port at US bases was lifted after the 2012 exercise.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Following the fall of Singapore and the decline of British power in Asia, Australia began to search for other partners to ensure its security.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Australia and New Zealand also felt threatened by the possibility of a resurgent Japan and the spread of communism to their North.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Percy Spender, Australia's minister for external affairs, sought a broader Pacific security agreement in 1950 which would include Australia, the UK, other Commonwealth countries and the United States.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The latter's participation was essential, with Spencer stating the agreement "would be meaningless without the United States".
[src:middle-ages/anzus] At this point however, both the UK and the US were uninterested in such an agreement, with both seeking to limit their engagement with Asia.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The beginning of the Korean War in mid-1950 changed American views.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Australia committed to the Korean War before the United Kingdom and continued to further court the Americans.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The United States was initially reluctant, but the need to strengthen the West against communism grew with the communist victory in the Chinese Civil War in 1949 and the 1950–1953 Korean War.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The treaty allayed antipodean fears that such a peace would allow Japan to threaten them again.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The United States was initially reluctant, with the president instead offering an informal guarantee of protection.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Instead, the text of the treaty mirrored the text of the Monroe Doctrine which stated that attacks on the American continent would be seen as "dangerous to its own peace and security".
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The resulting treaty was concluded at San Francisco on 1 September 1951, and entered into force on 29 April 1952.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The treaty itself was not a source of debate for over 30 years, with New Zealand participating as part of the British Commonwealth Forces in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency, followed by the Indonesia–Malaysia confrontation, and directly as part of ANZUS in the Vietnam War.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The Vietnam War was the first conflict New Zealand entered that did not involve the British or any other Commonwealth countries outside of Australia.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] As an ANZUS member New Zealand contributed military and non military assistance to the United States war effort in Vietnam from 1963 until 1975.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] New Zealand and Australian combat forces were withdrawn in 1972 and New Zealand non-military medical aid continued until 1975.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In 1983, the Reagan Administration approached Australia with proposals for testing the new generation of American intercontinental ballistic missiles, the MX missile.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] American test ranges in the Pacific were insufficient for testing the new long-range missiles and the United States military wished to use the Tasman Sea as a target area.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser of the Liberal Party had agreed to provide monitoring sites near Sydney for this purpose.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] However, in 1985, the newly elected Prime Minister Bob Hawke, of the Labor Party, withdrew Australia from the testing programme, sparking criticism from the Reagan Administration.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Hawke had been pressured into doing so by the left-wing faction of the Labor Party, which opposed the proposed MX missile test in the Tasman Sea.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The Labor left-wing faction also strongly sympathized with the New Zealand Fourth Labour Government's anti-nuclear policy and supported a South Pacific Nuclear Free Zone.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] To preserve its joint Australian-US military communications facilities, the Reagan Administration also had to assure the Hawke Government that those installations would not be used in the Strategic Defense Initiative project, which the Australian Labor Party strongly opposed.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Despite these disagreements, the Hawke Labor Government still remained supportive of the ANZUS security treaty.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] It also did not support its New Zealand counterpart's ban on nuclear-armed and nuclear-powered ships.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Following the ANZUS Split in February 1985, the Australian government also endorsed the Reagan Administration's plans to cancel trilateral military exercises and to postpone the ANZUS foreign ministers conference.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] However, it still continued to maintain bilateral military ties and continued to share intelligence information with New Zealand.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Unlike New Zealand, Australia continued to allow US warships to visit its ports and to participate in joint military exercises with the United States.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In 1985, the nature of the ANZUS alliance changed significantly.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Due to a current of anti-nuclear sentiment within New Zealand, tension had long been present between ANZUS members as the United States is a declared nuclear power.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] France, a naval power and a declared nuclear power, had been conducting nuclear tests on South Pacific Islands.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Following the victory of the New Zealand Labour Party in election in 1984, Prime Minister David Lange barred nuclear-powered or nuclear-armed ships from using New Zealand ports or entering New Zealand waters.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Reasons given were the dangers of nuclear weapons, continued French nuclear testing in the South Pacific, and opposition to US president Ronald Reagan's policy of aggressively confronting the Soviet Union.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Given that the United States Navy had a policy of deliberate ambiguity during the Cold War and refused to confirm or deny the presence of nuclear weapons aboard its warships and support ships, these laws essentially refused access to New Zealand ports for all United States Navy vessels.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In February 1985, a port-visit request by the United States for the guided-missile destroyer USS *Buchanan* was refused by New Zealand, as the *Buchanan* was capable of launching RUR-5 ASROC nuclear depth bombs.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] As this occurred after the government unofficially invited the United States to send a ship, the refusal of access was interpreted by the United States as a deliberate slight.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] According to opinion polls taken before the 1984 election, only 30 per cent of New Zealanders supported visits by US warships with a clear majority of 58 per cent opposed, and over 66 per cent of the population lived in locally declared nuclear-free zones.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The crisis made front-page headlines for weeks in many American newspapers.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] David Lange did not withdraw New Zealand from ANZUS, although his government's policy led to the US's decision to suspend its treaty obligations to New Zealand.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] An opinion poll in New Zealand in 1991, showed 54% of those sampled preferred to let the treaty lapse rather than accept visits again by nuclear-armed or nuclear-powered vessels.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] This law effectively made the entire country a nuclear-free zone.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Despite the ANZUS split, US Secretary of State George P.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Shultz maintained that the ANZUS structure was still in place, should NZ decide in the future to reverse its anti-nuclear policy and return to a fully operational defence relationship with the US.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] President Reagan also maintained in *NSDD 193* (National Security Decision Directive) that New Zealand still remained a "friend, but not an ally".
[src:middle-ages/anzus] On 10 July 1985, agents of the French Directorate-General for External Security bombed the Greenpeace protest vessel *Rainbow Warrior* in Auckland, causing one death.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The lack of condemnation by Western leaders to this violation of a friendly state's sovereignty caused a great deal of change in New Zealand's foreign and defence policy, and strengthened domestic opposition to the military application of nuclear technology in any form.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] New Zealand distanced itself from its traditional ally, the United States, and built relationships with small South Pacific countries, while retaining its good relations with Australia, and, to a lesser extent, the United Kingdom.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The suspension of New Zealand in ANZUS has had significant effect on New Zealand–United States relations and on New Zealand domestic policy.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The anti-nuclear policy has been a part of New Zealand political culture for years now.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] However, that has not stopped United States politicians from trying to change the policy.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Australia and New Zealand both provided military units, including special forces and naval ships, in support of the US-led "Operation Enduring Freedom" for support for anti-Taliban forces in response to the 11 September 2001 terrorist attacks.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Providing 1,550 troops, Australia was the largest non-NATO contributor of military personnel in Afghanistan.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In response to the War in Afghanistan, New Zealand sent transport aircraft, maritime patrol aircraft, and frigates to the Persian Gulf, and sent a very small number of soldiers, SAS soldiers, medical and assorted and peace-keeping forces to Afghanistan in 2001.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Despite Prime Minister Helen Clark being openly critical of American justifications for the 2003 Iraq war, New Zealand sent engineer troops to Iraq following the 2003 invasion.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] These troops were however officially engaged in reconstruction under UN Security Council Resolution 1483 and were non-combatant.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Between 1999 and 2003, the armed forces of Australia and New Zealand deployed together in a large scale operation in East Timor, to prevent pro-Indonesian militia from overturning a vote for independence on the region.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The United States provided only limited logistical support but the USS *Mobile Bay* provided air defence for the initial entry operation.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The operation was taken over by the United Nations.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] One topic that became prominent in the 2000s was the implications in the case of a hypothetical attack by the People's Republic of China against Taiwan, who would likely receive American support.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] While Australia has strong cultural and economic ties with the United States, it also has an increasingly important trade relationship with mainland China.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In August 2004, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer implied in Beijing that the treaty would likely not apply to that situation, but he was quickly corrected by Prime Minister John Howard.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Annual bilateral meetings between the US Secretary of State and the Australian Foreign Minister replaced annual meetings of the ANZUS Council of Foreign Ministers.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The first bilateral meeting was held in Canberra in 1985.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] At the second meeting, in San Francisco in 1986, the United States announced that it was suspending its treaty security obligations to New Zealand pending the restoration of port access.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Subsequent bilateral Australia–US Ministerial (AUSMIN) meetings have alternated between Australia and the United States.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Code § 2321k, United States president Bill Clinton, designated New Zealand as a major non-NATO ally, effectively recognizing New Zealand not only as a friend but also an ally.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The alliance engenders some political controversy in Australia.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Particularly after Australian involvement in the 2003 Iraq war, some quarters of Australian society have called for a re-evaluation of the relationship between the two nations.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Nonetheless, the alliance enjoyed broad support during the Cold War and continues to enjoy broad support in Australia.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] One commentator in Australia has argued that the treaty should be re-negotiated in the context of terrorism, the modern role of the United Nations and as a purely US–Australian alliance.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Australia is also a contributor to the National Missile Defense system.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In May 2006, US assistant secretary of state for east asia and pacific affairs Christopher Hill described the New Zealand anti-nuclear issue as "a bit of a relic", and signalled that the US wanted a closer defence relationship with New Zealand.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] He also praised New Zealand's involvement in Afghanistan and reconstruction in Iraq.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] "Rather than trying to change each other's minds on the nuclear issue, which is a bit of a relic, I think we should focus on things we can make work" he told an Australian newspaper.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] While there were signs of the nuclear dispute between the US and NZ thawing out, pressure from the United States increased in 2006 with US trade officials linking the repeal of the ban of American nuclear ships from New Zealand's ports to a potential free trade agreement between the two countries.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] On 4 February 2008, US trade representative Susan Schwab announced that the United States would join negotiations with four Asia–Pacific countries: Brunei, Chile, New Zealand and Singapore to be known as the "P-4".
[src:middle-ages/anzus] These countries already had a FTA called the Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership and the United States was looking to become involved in the "vitally important emerging Asia-Pacific region".
[src:middle-ages/anzus] A number of US-based organisations supported the negotiations including, but not limited to, the United States Chamber of Commerce, National Association of Manufacturers, National Foreign Trade Council, Emergency Committee for American Trade and Coalition of Service Industries.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In 2010, the United States and New Zealand signed the Wellington Declaration in Wellington, New Zealand, during a three-day visit by US secretary of state Hillary Clinton.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The signing of the declaration ended the ANZUS dispute of the previous 25 years.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] It was later revealed the US and New Zealand had resumed military co-operation in eight areas in 2007.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] On 16 November 2011, US president Obama and Australian prime minister Julia Gillard met in Canberra, Australia, to announce plans for a sustained new American presence on Australian soil.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] 2,500 American troops are to be deployed to Darwin, Australia.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] New Zealand and the United States signed the Washington Declaration on 19 June 2012 "to promote and strengthen closer bilateral defense and security cooperation".
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The Royal New Zealand Navy (RNZN) invited the United States Navy to send a vessel to participate in the RNZN's 75th Birthday Celebrations in Auckland over the weekend of 19–21 November 2016.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] The guided-missile destroyer USS *Sampson* became the first US warship to visit New Zealand in 33 years.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] New Zealand prime minister John Key granted approval for the ship's visit under the New Zealand Nuclear Free Zone, Disarmament, and Arms Control Act 1987, which requires that the Prime Minister has to be satisfied that any visiting ship is not nuclear armed or powered.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] Following the 7.8 magnitude Kaikōura earthquake on 14 November 2016 the *Sampson* and other naval ships from Australia, Canada, Japan and Singapore were diverted to proceed directly to Kaikōura to provide humanitarian assistance.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] In late 2021 Australia, the UK and the USA signed the AUKUS agreement, a trilateral security partnership between Australia, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:middle-ages/anzus] New Zealand did not participate and any nuclear submarines developed under the pact will be banned from New Zealand waters under their existing nuclear restrictions.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] AUKUS is widely seen as a response to the perception among its members that the People's Republic of China poses a threat to the Indo-Pacific region.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Chinese government said, when the partnership was announced, that it risked "severely damaging regional peace" and had a "cold-war mentality".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] A direct result of the creation of the partnership was Australia's controversial cancellation of a French-Australian submarine contract worth €56 billion (A$90 billion).
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Australian government only gave the French government a few hours' notice of this before the public announcement of AUKUS.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Australian government agreed to a €555 million (US$584 million) compensation settlement with French defence contractor Naval Group.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In 2009, two years after the start of the project to replace the Royal Australian Navy's conventionally-powered *Collins*-class submarines, the Australian Defence White Paper stated: "The Government has ruled out nuclear propulsion for these submarines".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The design was based on the latest French nuclear-powered attack submarine, the Barracuda class, which required converting the nuclear propulsion to conventional propulsion.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Another difference was that Australia chose to equip it with a United States Navy combat system and torpedo with Lockheed Martin Australia selected to integrate them into the design.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australia typically requires that part of their vessels be built there, which increases the cost.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In this case it corresponded to 60 per cent of the contract value, with France handling the technology transfer.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In 2019, Australia signed a strategic partnership agreement with Naval Group to design and construct twelve submarines to be built in Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] However, the project was beset by delays and cost overruns, leading to uncertainty and tension behind the scenes.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The revised cost, including inflation during the length of the program, was A$90 billion (€56 billion).
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In February 2021, an initial design plan was rejected as being too expensive, and Naval Group were given until September to improve their proposal.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] At a Senate inquiry in early June 2021, with delays ongoing, Defence Secretary Greg Moriarty revealed under questioning that he had considered making contingency plans if the French project was to fail, admitting that there had been ongoing problems for over a year.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Two weeks later, Australian prime minister Scott Morrison met French president Emmanuel Macron in Paris and expressed concern about the project going off track, to which Macron replied that France was giving "full and complete" commitment and would proceed "further and faster if possible".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Less than three weeks later, Australia decided to publicly cancel the contract with Naval Group for the *Attack* class submarines despite having already spent about A$2.4 billion on the French project.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] It was expected that Australia would have to pay hundreds of millions of euros in penalties for cancelling the contract.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The contract contained "control gates" with "off-ramps" at which point Australia could withdraw from the contract.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Australian Department of Defence wrote to Naval Group on the same day the security partnership was announced.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The French Ministry of Defence claim the department told them that "they were satisfied with the submarine's achievable performance and with the progress of the program." Naval Group said that Australia "terminated the contract for convenience".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Morrison said that Australia now required a nuclear-powered submarine which has clear advantages of greater endurance, speed, power, stealth and carrying capacity than a conventionally-powered submarine, based on changes in the strategic situation in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] However, Johnson later told parliament that the move was not intended to be "adversarial towards any other power".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] United States secretary of state Antony Blinken and United States secretary of defense Lloyd Austin said that Australia did not have any "reciprocal requirements" as a consequence of the US sharing nuclear submarine propulsion technology such as Australia hosting intermediate-range missiles.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Under the partnership, the US and UK will share nuclear propulsion technology with Australia, as they have done with each other since 1958 under the US–UK Mutual Defence Agreement.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Royal Australian Navy (RAN) will acquire at least eight nuclear-powered submarines armed with conventional weapons.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The basic design and key technologies will be decided by the Australian Nuclear-Powered Submarine Task Force an 18-month Department of Defence research project headed by Vice Admiral Jonathan Mead, begun in September 2021 with assistance from the US and UK.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australia will extend the life of its *Collins* class submarines that the *Attack* class was due to replace and may consider leasing or buying nuclear-powered submarines from the US or the UK in the interim until the delivery of its future nuclear powered submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Also in the interim, Australian Defence Minister Peter Dutton said that Australia will have regular visits by US and UK nuclear-powered submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australia considered purchasing French nuclear submarines which use nuclear reactors fuelled by low-enriched uranium at less than 6%.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] However, French reactor designs have to be refuelled every ten years, and Australia does not have a civil nuclear capability with nuclear energy prohibited.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In contrast, American and British designs power the submarines for the expected life of the submarines using nuclear reactors fuelled by highly enriched uranium (HEU) at 93% enrichment.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Currently, six countries have nuclear submarines, the five permanent members of the UN Security Council (China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom and the United States) and India.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The New York Times reported that Australia will probably buy HEU from the US for the nuclear reactor that powers the submarine.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The United States' naval reactors are all pressurized water reactors (PWR).
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The latest UK propulsion system is the Rolls-Royce PWR3 that will power the Royal Navy's (RN) new *Dreadnought*-class submarines currently being built and is "based on a US design but using UK reactor technology".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] US officials have said that sharing nuclear propulsion technology with Australia is a "one-off" and that they have no "intention of extending this to other countries".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] South Korea, also a US treaty ally, has had ambitions to acquire nuclear-powered submarines since 2017 and was reportedly refused US assistance in September 2020 because of nuclear non-proliferation.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] On 22 November 2021, Australia, the US and the UK signed the *Exchange of Naval Nuclear Propulsion Information Agreement* (ENNPIA) treaty.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The treaty permits the disclosure of information by the US and the UK to Australia and its use.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The US is restricted by the Atomic Energy Act of 1946 from sharing information without an agreement and the UK is also restricted by the 1958 US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement unless authorised.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The treaty was considered in Australia by the Parliament's Joint Standing Committee on Treaties, in the UK by the Parliament and in the US by Congress.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The ENNPIA treaty entered into force on 8 February 2022.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] On 31 August 2022, the UK announced that Australian submariners would receive training aboard *Astute*-class submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] On 13 March 2023, AUKUS announced that a new nuclear powered submarine class would be built in the UK and Australia to be called the SSN-AUKUS, also known as the SSN-A.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The US intends to sell Australia three nuclear-powered *Virginia* class submarines, subject to congressional approval, to ensure there is no capability gap as the *Collins* class submarines are retired, with the potential to sell up to two more if needed.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] RAN personnel will be embedded in the RN and USN to receive nuclear training and at UK and US submarine industrial bases.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The SSN-AUKUS class will based on the UK SSNR design already under development.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The RN is planned to receive its first SSN-AUKUS class submarine as early as the late 2030s.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The RAN is planned to receive their first submarine in the early 2040s.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australia will reportedly build five SSN-AUKUS submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The RAN is planned to receive their first *Virginia* class submarine from the US in the early 2030s.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Australian Submarine Agency was established on 1 July 2023.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] It has the role of managing the Australian nuclear submarine program, and includes personnel posted to the UK and US.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Lincoln Reifsteck USN, the USN's AUKUS integration and acquisition program manager, talked at the Naval Submarine League's annual symposium.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] He said that, in 2032 and 2035, the US will sell to Australia in-service Block IV *Virginia* class submarines, the first of which was commissioned in 2020, and the final will likely commission around 2026.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Thus, Australia would receive submarines with between six and 15 years' worth of use, out of their designed service life of 33 years.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] He also said that the US would sell a new Block VII boat to Australia in 2038, the Block VIIs being the original *Virginia* class length without the Virginia Payload Module, set to begin construction in FY2029.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In August 2024, Australian prime minister Anthony Albanese, made undisclosed "political commitments" with its AUKUS partners in an agreement for the transfer of naval nuclear technology to Australia, sparking concerns about the potential for high-level radioactive waste to be stored in the country.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The White House confirmed that Australia, the UK, and the US reached a significant milestone in their cooperation, essential for Australia's future nuclear-powered submarine capabilities.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Despite assurances from the government, critics, including the Greens, warned of possible loopholes that could lead to uranium enrichment and radioactive waste management in Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] On 1 June 2025, the UK government announced that it will build up to twelve SSN-AUKUS submarines to replace the Royal Navy's seven *Astute-*class attack submarines from the late 2030s.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The announcement also said that there will be a major expansion of industrial capability at BAE Systems Submarines at Barrow and at Rolls-Royce Submarines at Derby, with a new boat scheduled to be built every eighteen months.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] On 26 July 2025, the UK and Australian governments signed the **Geelong Treaty**, a 50-year bilateral defence agreement to facilitate bilateral cooperation on the construction of Australia's SSN-AUKUS submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] On 30 May 2026, at an AUKUS Defence Minister's Meeting held in Singapore it was announced that the third *Virginia-*class boat that Australia is planned to receive will now be an in-service Block IV boat the same as the first two.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] This will simplify fleet training and maintenance for Australia and save them significant costs.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] AUKUS Pillar 2 encompasses a wide array of activities (including many commonly referred to by the US Department of Defense as international armaments cooperation).
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] There may include information and personnel exchange, cooperative research, development, testing, and evaluation, and joint production.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In contrast to Pillar 1 activities, which will take decades to deliver results, Pillar 2 is likely to produce more immediate capability improvements.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Undersea capabilities, in the context of AUKUS, refer to systems and technologies that operate underwater but are not crewed submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Defence Minister's meeting on 30 May 2026 announced that the first signature project of Pillar 2 would be cutting-edge sensors, payloads and weapons systems for UUVs with delivery to commence in 2027.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] As part of the Quantum Technologies working group, the AUKUS nations have established the AUKUS Quantum Arrangement (AQuA), an initiative to coordinate U.S., British, and Australian RDT&E efforts concerning quantum technologies.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Initial AQuA efforts were expected to focus on developing alternate solutions for position, navigation, and timing (similar to current Global Positioning System capability) through trials and experimentation through 2025.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The announcement of AUKUS included the stated aim of improving "joint capabilities and interoperability.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] We've always been interoperable, but this aims at much more.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] From artificial intelligence to advanced technology the US, UK and Australia will now be able to cost save by increasing platform sharing and innovation costs.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] *Engineering & Technology* also pointed to the March 2021 statement of the US National Security Commission on AI, of the imperative to intensify local efforts but also "rally our closest allies and partners to defend and compete in the coming era of AI-accelerated competition and conflict".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Under the partnership, the three countries will cooperate to accelerate development of hypersonic missiles and defence against such missiles.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Hypersonic and counter-hypersonic cooperation was one of four additional areas of cooperation announced on 5 April 2022.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australia and the US have been cooperating on the development of hypersonic missiles since 2020 after signing an agreement to "flight test full-size prototype hypersonic cruise missiles" under the Southern Cross Integrated Flight Research Experiment (SCIFiRE).
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In addition, the U.S., British, and Australian governments have established a number of initiatives designed to support Pillar 2 efforts as a whole, such as the AUKUS Advanced Capabilities Industry Forum and the AUKUS Defense Investors Network.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Since the announcement of "Pillar II" of AUKUS, there has been persistent speculation that Japan will eventually join the partnership; American Ambassador to Japan Rahm Emanuel wrote that Japan was "about to become the first additional Pillar II partner" in *The Wall Street Journal* on 3 April 2024.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] On 7 April 2024, the *Financial Times* reported that AUKUS defence ministers will announce on 8 April 2024 that they will launch talks related to the expansion of Pillar II of the alliance.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In September 2024, the leaders of Australia, the UK and the US issued a joint statement announcing that AUKUS partners and Japan were exploring opportunities to improve interoperability of their maritime autonomous systems as an initial area of cooperation.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] New Zealand has agreed to officially explore the potential benefits of joining Pillar 2.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In March 2023, New Zealand's defence minister Andrew Little said New Zealand had been offered the opportunity to discuss joining AUKUS for the non-submarine co-operation areas.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] New Zealand has indicated it was "willing to explore" the proposal.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In July 2023, US Secretary of State Antony Blinken told New Zealand reporters that the “door is open” for New Zealand, as well as other countries, to join the security partnership.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In December 2023, following the formation of a new government, Prime Minister Christopher Luxon said that New Zealand was open to joining the non-nuclear pillar of the AUKUS agreement during a state visit to Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In February 2024, Australia agreed to brief New Zealand on Pillar 2 developments following a joint bilateral meeting between Australian and New Zealand foreign and defence ministers in Melbourne.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australian Defence Minister Richard Marles confirmed that Australia would send officials to brief their New Zealand counterparts on Pillar 2.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The four ministers also issued a joint statement expressing concerns about human rights violations in Xinjiang, Tibet and Hong Kong.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In response to the joint Australian-NZ bilateral meeting, the Chinese Embassy in Wellington issued a statement deploring critical statements about China's internal affairs and describing AUKUS as "counter to the letter and spirit of the international nuclear non-proliferation regime".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In September 2024, the leaders of Australia, the UK and the US issued a joint statement announcing that they were consulting with Canada, New Zealand, and South Korea to identify possibilities for collaboration on advanced capabilities under AUKUS Pillar II.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty allows non-nuclear-weapon states to produce the highly enriched uranium for naval reactor fuel.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Nevertheless, the agreement to transfer US or UK nuclear submarine technology including possibly highly enriched uranium has been described as an act of nuclear proliferation, and has been criticised by scholars and politicians.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In the *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists*, scholar Sébastien Philippe criticised AUKUS and wrote "we can now expect the proliferation of very sensitive military nuclear technology in the coming years, with literally tons of new nuclear materials under loose or no international safeguards".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Acton of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace wrote that "the nonproliferation implications of the AUKUS submarine deal are both negative and serious.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] For Australia to operate nuclear-powered submarines, it will have to become the first non-nuclear-weapon state to exercise a loophole that allows it to remove nuclear material from the inspection system of the International Atomic Energy Agency.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] I have no real concerns that Australia will misuse this material itself, but I am concerned that this removal will set a damaging precedent.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australia and Brazil would be the first countries without nuclear weapons to have nuclear-powered submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] This would not apply in the case of Brazil because the reactor will use low enriched uranium at 7% concentration.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] 20% is the minimum level required to make a nuclear weapon.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Former Labor prime minister Paul Keating condemned the deal, saying "This arrangement would witness a further dramatic loss of Australian sovereignty, as material dependency on the United States robbed Australia of any freedom or choice in any engagement Australia may deem appropriate".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Former Labor prime minister Kevin Rudd warned against overly obtrusive criticism of China and recommended that Australia focus on quietly improving military capability.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Former Liberal prime minister Malcolm Turnbull, who had signed the original deal for the *Attack* class submarines called the decision to scrap the deal "an appalling episode in Australia's international affairs and the consequences of it will endure to our disadvantage for a very long time".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] He called the actions of his successor as deceitful and that it would damage Australia as foreign nations would no longer be able to trust Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Abbott said that Australia would be safer as a result, and cited China's increasing naval firepower as a justification for the deal.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The Australian defence minister at the time, Peter Dutton, responded by saying that Australia wanted peace and stability and "an opportunity for Indonesia, Vietnam and Sri Lanka and Korea to continue to develop".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Dutton further dismissed "outbursts from China" and said that Australia was a "proud democracy" committed to "enduring peace and this collaboration makes it a safer region ... no amount of propaganda can dismiss the facts".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Australian Greens leader Adam Bandt criticised the deal, saying that it escalates tensions in the region and "makes Australia less safe".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Prime Minister at the time, Boris Johnson, said that the deal would create "hundreds of high-skilled jobs" and "preserve security and stability around the world" but said that the relationship with France was "rock solid".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Conservative MP Tom Tugendhat said: "After years of bullying and trade hostility, and watching regional neighbours like the Philippines see encroachment into their waters, Australia didn't have a choice, and nor did the US or UK [to make the deal]".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Former prime minister Theresa May questioned whether the UK would be forced into a war with China should Taiwan be invaded.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Johnson responded to French anger on 21 September by saying "I just think it's time for some of our dearest friends around the world to prenez un grip about this and donnez-moi un break"; the latter being broken French for "get a grip and give me a break".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In 2026, the Defence Select Committee inquiry on AUKUS found that the political leadership of the programme had faded and that the UK commitment to *Astute*-class submarine visits to Australia had placed severe pressure on the overstretched Royal Navy.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] Responsibility for AUKUS had been transferred from the Cabinet Office to the Ministry of Defence, though the view that Prime Ministerial leadership would be important to maintaining the political impetus to deliver AUKUS was reported.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] The MOD had forecast that the UK nuclear workforce (defence plus civil) will need to increase by 40,000 by 2030 to support AUKUS and the wider demands on the Defence Nuclear Enterprise.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] To 2026, the UK government had committed £16 billion to developing AUKUS: long lead components for SSN-AUKUS, BAE and Rolls-Royce plant upgrades, and the Rolls-Royce nuclear reactors for submarines.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] It noted that trilateral progress on advanced technology under Pillar 2 had been inadequate and was losing credibility.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] President Joe Biden stated that the deal was a way to "address both the current strategic environment in the (Indo-Pacific) region and how it may evolve".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] After a call between the French and US presidents, the White House acknowledged the crisis could have been averted if there had been open consultations between allies.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] It was agreed the process would continue in such manner.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p01] In June 2025, the United States Department of Defense launched a review to inform whether to modify or cancel the AUKUS agreement with Australia and the United Kingdom, after a push by the Under Secretary of Defense for Policy, Elbridge Colby.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] On 12 April 2022, *Sankei Shimbun* reported that the United States, United Kingdom, and Australia were inquiring about Japan's participation in the security framework of AUKUS.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The newspaper added that the aim of said negotiations was related to the incorporation of Japanese hypersonic weapon development and the strengthening of electronic warfare capabilities.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The US denied inviting Japan into the security alliance, with Jen Psaki stating that Sankei Shimbun's report was "inaccurate".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] This was followed by another denial from Hirokazu Matsuno, the Japanese chief cabinet secretary.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] On 10 December 2022, Australia's Minister for Defence announced their desire for Japan to join the partnership.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] On 14 March 2023, Japanese prime minister Kishida Fumio expressed his support for Australia's planned acquisition of US-made nuclear-powered submarines under the AUKUS partnership.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The French government received official notification from Australia that the *Attack* class submarine project was to be cancelled only a few hours before it was publicly announced.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] *Le Monde* reported that the original cost of the project in 2016 was €35 billion of which €8 billion (A$12 billion) was to go to French companies.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The project was reportedly going to employ 4,000 people in France over six years at Naval Group and its 200 subcontractors.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The French government was angered by both the cancellation of the *Attack* class submarine project and not being made aware of the negotiations that led to the AUKUS agreement.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] In a joint statement, French foreign minister Jean-Yves Le Drian and armed forces minister Florence Parly expressed disappointment at Australia's decision to abandon their joint submarine program with France.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] On 31 October 2021, at the G20 summit in Rome, Macron was asked whether he thought that PM Morrison lied about the French submarine contract, to which Macron responded "I don't think, I know".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The French Ambassador also criticised Morrison on the basis that he lied about the former contract.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Le Drian further stated in a radio interview that the contract termination was a "stab in the back".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] On 17 September, France recalled its ambassadors from Australia and the US, Jean-Pierre Thébault and Philippe Étienne respectively.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Despite tension in the past, France had never before withdrawn its ambassador to the United States.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] In a statement, Le Drian said that the "exceptional decision is justified by the exceptional gravity of the [AUKUS] announcements" and that the snap cancellation of the submarine contract "constitute[d] unacceptable behaviour between allies and partners".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] French president Emmanuel Macron has not commented but is reported to have been "furious" about the turn of events.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] In response to questions about the Australia-EU trade deal currently being negotiated, French secretary of state for European affairs Clément Beaune stated that he doesn't see how France can trust Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Arnaud Danjean, a French MEP, said that "Australians can expect more than a delay in concluding the Free Trade Agreement with the EU".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] French Lowy Institute policy analyst Hervé Lemahieu said the diplomatic damage from the cancellation will take years to repair and leave a lasting legacy of mistrust".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] After a call between the French and US presidents, the French ambassador returned to the US on 30 September.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Beaune described the United Kingdom as a junior partner and vassal of the United States due to the partnership, saying in an interview: "Our British friends explained to us they were leaving the EU to create Global Britain.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] We can see that this is a return into the American lap and a form of accepted vassalisation." Le Drian stated that "We have recalled our ambassadors to [Canberra and Washington] to re-evaluate the situation.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] So there is no need to bring our ambassador back to explain." A Franco-British defence summit was cancelled.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Some opposition politicians in France, such as Xavier Bertrand, Jordan Bardella, and Fabien Roussel, criticised the French government and demanded that France leave NATO, with Christian Jacob as well as demanding a parliamentary inquiry.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] A foreign ministers meeting between France, Germany, the UK, and the US had been postponed, and a ministerial meeting between Australia, France, and India was cancelled.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] France however, contacted India to talk about strengthening their cooperation in the Indo-Pacific.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] France's foreign commerce minister declined a meeting with his Australian counterpart.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] French president Macron said that Europe needs to stop being naïve when it comes to defending its interests and build its own military capacity.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Following the ousting of Scott Morrison's government after the 2022 Australian federal election, the new Labor government led by Prime Minister Anthony Albanese agreed to a €555 million (US$584 million) settlement with French defence contractor Naval Group.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] In response, French defence minister Lecornu said that France aims to rebuild its relationship with Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] In addition, Albanese announced plans to travel to France to reset bilateral relations between the two countries.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The exclusion of France from AUKUS has been conceptualised within the longue durée of the fractious relationship between France and the Anglosphere, potentially reducing scope for coordination in the Indo-Pacific in the short term.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Zhao also said "The three countries should discard the Cold War zero-sum mentality and narrow geopolitical perspective".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Spokesperson Hua Chunying said "China is firmly opposed to the US, the UK and Australia's malicious exploitation of loopholes in the Nuclear non-proliferation treaty and the International Atomic Energy Agency safeguards mechanism".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] It further told Australia to avoid "provocation" or else China would "certainly punish it with no mercy", and concluded "Thus, Australian troops are also most likely to be the first batch of western soldiers to waste their lives in the South China Sea".
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The PRC ambassador to France Lu Shaye urged the new alliance to fulfill their nuclear non proliferation obligations and said Asia-Pacific needs jobs, not submarines, and urged France to boost cooperation.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen told CNN that "one of our member states has been treated in a way that is not acceptable. ...
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] We want to know what happened and why." The EU also demanded an apology from Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] President of the European Council Charles Michel denounced a "lack of transparency and loyalty" by the US.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] The EU said the crisis affects the whole union.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Preparations for a new EU-US trade and technology council between the US and EU were postponed.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] France eventually dropped their opposition to these talks which took place in Pittsburgh on 29 September 2021.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] France also attempted to delay the free trade talks between the EU and Australia.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Key advocates for the TTC talks included EU's digital chief Margrethe Vestager, who favors open markets, and EU trade chief Valdis Dombrovskis from Latvia, who views the US alliance and NATO as a vital counterweight to Russia and China.
[src:middle-ages/aukus-p02] Lithuanian deputy European Affairs Minister Arnoldas Prankevicius proclaimed "What is important is to keep trans-Atlantic unity, because we believe this is our biggest strength and biggest value, especially vis-à-vis such countries as Russia and China".
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the history of Europe, the **Middle Ages** or **medieval period** lasted approximately from the 5th to late 15th centuries, comparable with the post-classical period of global history.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The medieval period is the middle epoch of the three traditional divisions of Western history: classical antiquity, the medieval period, and the modern period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The medieval period is itself subdivided into the Early, High, and Late Middle Ages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Middle Ages began with the fall of the Western Roman Empire and transitioned into the Modern age during the Renaissance, the Reformation, the European wars of religion, and the Age of Discovery.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Early Modernity is a single term adopted to describe this end-stage of the period, during which medieval Europe shades into the modern period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Population decline, counterurbanisation, the collapse of centralised authority, invasions, and mass migrations of tribes had begun in late antiquity (c. ~3rd–8th centuries) and lasted into the Early Middle Ages (c.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The large-scale movements of the Migration Period, including various Germanic peoples, formed new kingdoms in what remained of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the 7th century, North Africa and the Middle East—once part of the Byzantine Empire—came under the rule of the Umayyad Caliphate, an Islamic empire, after conquest by Muhammad's successors.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Although there were substantial changes in society and political structures, the break with classical antiquity was incomplete.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The still-sizeable Byzantine Empire, Rome's direct continuation, survived in the Eastern Mediterranean and remained a major power.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The empire's law code, the *Corpus Juris Civilis* or "Code of Justinian", was rediscovered in Northern Italy in the 11th century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the West, most kingdoms incorporated the few extant Roman institutions.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Monasteries were founded as campaigns to Christianise the remaining pagans across Europe continued.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Franks, under the Carolingian dynasty, briefly established the Carolingian Empire during the later 8th and early 9th centuries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] It covered much of Western Europe but later succumbed to the pressures of internal civil wars combined with external invasions: Vikings from the north, Magyars from the east, and Saracens from the south.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] During the High Middle Ages, which began after 1000, the population of Europe increased significantly as technological and agricultural innovations allowed trade to flourish and the Medieval Warm Period climate change allowed crop yields to increase.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] This period also saw the collapse of the unified Christian church with the East–West Schism of 1054.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Crusades, first preached in 1095, were military attempts by Western European Christians to regain control of the Holy Land from Muslims.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Kings became the heads of centralised nation-states, reducing crime and violence but making the ideal of a unified Christendom more distant.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Intellectual life was marked by scholasticism, a philosophy that emphasised joining faith to reason, and by the founding of universities.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The theology of Thomas Aquinas, the paintings of Giotto, the poetry of Dante and Chaucer, the travels of Marco Polo, and the Gothic architecture of cathedrals such as Chartres are among the outstanding achievements toward the end of this period and into the Late Middle Ages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Late Middle Ages was marked by difficulties and calamities, including famine, plague, and war, which significantly diminished the population of Europe; between 1347 and 1350, the Black Death killed about a third of Europeans.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Controversy, heresy, and the Western Schism within the Catholic Church paralleled the interstate conflict, civil strife, and peasant revolts that occurred in the kingdoms.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Cultural and technological developments transformed European society, concluding the Late Middle Ages and beginning the early modern period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Middle Ages is one of the three major periods in the most enduring scheme for analysing European history: classical civilisation or antiquity, the Middle Ages and the modern period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The "Middle Ages" first appears in Latin in 1469 as *media tempestas* or "middle season".
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In early usage, there were many variants, including *medium aevum*, or "middle age", first recorded in 1604, and *media saecula*, or "middle centuries", first recorded in 1625.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The adjective "medieval" (or sometimes "mediaeval" or "mediæval"), meaning pertaining to the Middle Ages, derives from *medium aevum*.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Medieval writers divided history into periods such as the "Six Ages" or the "Four Empires" and considered their time to be the last before the end of the world.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] When referring to their own times, they spoke of them as being "modern".
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the 1330s, the Italian humanist and poet Petrarch referred to pre-Christian times as *antiqua* ('ancient') and to the Christian period as *nova* ('new').
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Petrarch regarded the post-Roman centuries as "dark" compared to the "light" of classical antiquity.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Leonardo Bruni was the first historian to use tripartite periodisation in his *History of the Florentine People* (1442), with a middle period "between the fall of the Roman Empire and the revival of city life sometime in late eleventh and twelfth centuries".
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Tripartite periodisation became standard after the 17th-century German historian Christoph Cellarius divided history into three periods: ancient, medieval, and modern.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The most commonly given starting point for the Middle Ages is around 500, with the date of 476 first used by Bruni--mapping to the removal of the last (native) Roman emperor in the West from power and his replacement by a German chieftain.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Later starting dates are sometimes used in the outer parts of Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] For Europe as a whole, 1500 is often considered to be the end of the Middle Ages, but there is no universally agreed upon end date.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Depending on the context, events such as the conquest of Constantinople by the Turks in 1453, Christopher Columbus's first voyage to the Americas in 1492, or the Reformation in 1517 are sometimes used.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] English historians often use the Battle of Bosworth Field in 1485 to mark the end of the period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] For Spain, dates commonly used are the death of King Ferdinand II in 1516, the death of Queen Isabella I of Castile in 1504, or the conquest of Granada in 1492.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 1648, marking the end of the European wars of religion, might be considered an upper-bound that preserves the tripartite schema of the terminology (classical antiquity, the medieval, and the modern).
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the end of the Thirty Years War, this transition has been accomplished in a geopolitical sense and the territory previously known as Christendom begins to be called Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Historians from Romance-speaking countries tend to divide the Middle Ages into two parts: an earlier "High" and later "Low" period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] English-speaking historians, following their German counterparts, generally subdivide the Middle Ages into three intervals: "Early", "High", and "Late".
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the 19th century, the entire Middle Ages were often referred to as the "Dark Ages", but with the adoption of these subdivisions, use of this term was restricted to the Early Middle Ages, at least among historians.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Roman Empire reached its greatest territorial extent during the 2nd century AD; the following two centuries witnessed the slow decline of Roman control over its outlying territories.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Economic issues, including inflation, and external pressure on the frontiers combined to create the Crisis of the Third Century, with emperors coming to the throne only to be rapidly replaced by new usurpers.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Military expenses increased steadily during the 3rd century, mainly in response to the war with the Sasanian Empire, which revived in the middle of the 3rd century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The army doubled in size, and cavalry and smaller units replaced the Roman legion as the main tactical unit.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The need for revenue led to increased taxes and a decline in numbers of the curial, or landowning, class, and decreasing numbers of them willing to shoulder the burdens of holding office in their native towns.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] More bureaucrats were needed in the central administration to deal with the needs of the army, which led to complaints from civilians that there were more tax-collectors in the empire than tax-payers.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 284–305) split the empire into separately administered eastern and western halves in 286; the empire was not considered divided by its inhabitants or rulers, as legal and administrative promulgations in one division were considered valid in the other.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 330, after a period of civil war, Constantine the Great (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 306–337) refounded the city of Byzantium as the newly renamed eastern capital, Constantinople.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Diocletian's reforms strengthened the governmental bureaucracy, reformed taxation, and strengthened the army, which bought the empire time but did not resolve the problems it was facing: excessive taxation, a declining birthrate, and pressures on its frontiers, among others.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Civil war between rival emperors became common in the middle of the 4th century, diverting soldiers from the empire's frontier forces and allowing invaders to encroach.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] For much of the 4th century, Roman society stabilised in a new form that differed from the earlier classical period, with a widening gulf between the rich and poor, and a decline in the vitality of the smaller towns.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Another change was the Christianisation, or conversion of the empire to Christianity, a gradual process that lasted from the 2nd to the 5th centuries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 376, the Goths, fleeing from the Huns, received permission from Emperor Valens (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 364–378) to settle in the Roman province of Thracia in the Balkans.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The settlement did not go smoothly, and the Goths began to raid and plunder when Roman officials mishandled the situation.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Valens, attempting to put down the disorder, was killed fighting the Goths at the Battle of Adrianople on 9 August 378.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In addition to the threat from such tribal confederacies in the north, internal divisions within the empire, especially within the Christian Church, caused problems.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 400, the Visigoths invaded the Western Roman Empire and, although briefly forced back from Italy, in 410 sacked the city of Rome.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 406 the Alans, Vandals, and Suevi crossed into Gaul; over the next three years they spread across Gaul and in 409 crossed the Pyrenees Mountains into modern-day Spain.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Migration Period began, when various peoples, initially largely Germanic peoples, moved across Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Franks, Alemanni, and the Burgundians all ended up in northern Gaul while the Angles, Saxons, and Jutes settled in Britain, and the Vandals went on to cross the strait of Gibraltar after which they conquered the province of Africa.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the 430s the Huns began invading the empire; their king Attila (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 434–453) led invasions into the Balkans in 442 and 447, Gaul in 451, and Italy in 452.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Hunnic threat remained until Attila's death in 453, when the Hunnic confederation he led fell apart.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] These invasions by the tribes completely changed the political and demographic nature of what had been the Western Roman Empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the end of the 5th century, the western section of the empire was divided into smaller political units ruled by the tribes that had invaded in the early part of the century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The deposition of the last emperor of the west, Romulus Augustulus, in 476 has traditionally marked the end of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By 493 the Italian peninsula was conquered by the Ostrogoths.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Eastern Roman Empire, often referred to as the Byzantine Empire after the fall of its western counterpart, had little ability to assert control over the lost western territories.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 527–565) was the sole, and temporary, exception.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The political structure of Western Europe changed with the end of the united Roman Empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Although the movements of peoples during this period are usually described as "invasions", they were not just military expeditions but migrations of entire peoples into the empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Such movements were aided by the refusal of the Western Roman elites to support the army or pay the taxes that would have allowed the military to suppress the migration.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The emperors of the 5th century were often controlled by military strongmen such as Stilicho (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 516), who were partly or fully of non-Roman background.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] When the line of Western emperors ceased, many of the kings who replaced them were from the same background.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Intermarriage between the new kings and the Roman elites was common.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] This led to a fusion of Roman culture with the customs of the invading tribes, including the popular assemblies that allowed free male tribal members more say in political matters than was common in the Roman state.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Material artefacts left by the Romans and the invaders are often similar, and tribal items were often modelled on Roman objects.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Much of the scholarly and written culture of the new kingdoms was also based on Roman intellectual traditions.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] An important difference was the new polities' gradual loss of tax revenue.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Many new political entities no longer supported their armies through taxes; instead, they relied on granting them land or rents.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] This meant there was less need for large tax revenues, so the taxation systems decayed.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Warfare was common between and within the kingdoms.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Slavery declined as the supply weakened, and society became more rural.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Between the 5th and 8th centuries, new peoples and individuals filled the political void left by the centralised Roman government.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Ostrogoths, a Gothic tribe, settled in Roman Italy in the late fifth century under Theoderic the Great (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 526) and set up a kingdom marked by its co-operation between the Italians and the Ostrogoths, at least until the last years of Theodoric's reign.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Burgundians settled in Gaul, and after an earlier realm was destroyed by the Huns in 436, formed a new kingdom in the 440s.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Between today's Geneva and Lyon, it grew to become the realm of Burgundy in the late 5th and early 6th centuries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Elsewhere in Gaul, the Franks and Celtic Britons set up small polities.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Francia was centred in northern Gaul, and the first king of whom much is known is Childeric I (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] His grave was discovered in 1653 and is remarkable for its grave goods, which included weapons and a large quantity of gold.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 509–511), the founder of the Merovingian dynasty, the Frankish kingdom expanded and converted to Christianity.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Britons, related to the natives of Britannia – modern-day Great Britain – settled in what is now Brittany.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Other monarchies were established by the Visigothic Kingdom in the Iberian Peninsula, the Suebi in northwestern Iberia, and the Vandal Kingdom in North Africa.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the sixth century, the Lombards settled in Northern Italy, replacing the Ostrogothic kingdom with a grouping of duchies that occasionally selected a king to rule over them all.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the late sixth century, this arrangement had been replaced by a permanent monarchy, the Kingdom of the Lombards.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The invasions brought new ethnic groups to Europe, although some regions received a larger influx of new peoples than others.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In Gaul, for instance, the invaders settled much more extensively in the north-east than in the south-west.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Slavs settled in Central and Eastern Europe and the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Changes in languages accompanied the settlement of peoples.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Latin, the literary language of the Western Roman Empire, was gradually replaced by vernacular languages, which evolved from Latin but were distinct from it, collectively known as Romance languages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] These changes from Latin to the new languages took many centuries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Greek remained the language of the Byzantine Empire, but the migrations of the Slavs added Slavic languages to Eastern Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] As Western Europe witnessed the formation of new kingdoms, the Eastern Roman Empire remained intact and experienced an economic revival that lasted into the early 7th century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] There were fewer invasions of the eastern section of the empire; most occurred in the Balkans.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Peace with the Sasanian Empire, Rome's traditional enemy, lasted most of the 5th century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Eastern Empire was marked by closer relations between the political state and the Christian Church, with doctrinal matters assuming an importance in Eastern politics that they did not have in Western Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Legal developments included the codification of Roman law; the first effort—the *Codex Theodosianus*—was completed in 438.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 527–565), another compilation took place—the *Corpus Juris Civilis*.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Justinian also oversaw the construction of the Hagia Sophia in Constantinople and the reconquest of North Africa from the Vandals and Italy from the Ostrogoths, under Belisarius (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The conquest of Italy was not complete, as a deadly outbreak of plague in 542 led to the rest of Justinian's reign concentrating on defensive measures rather than further conquests.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] At the Emperor's death, the Byzantines had control of most of Italy, North Africa, and a small foothold in southern Spain.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the Eastern Empire, the Slavs' slow infiltration of the Balkans added further difficulty for Justinian's successors.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] It began gradually, but by the late 540s, Slavic tribes were in Thrace and Illyrium and had defeated an imperial army near Adrianople in 551.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the 560s, the Avars began to expand from their base on the north bank of the Danube; by the end of the 6th century, they were the dominant power in Central Europe and routinely able to force the Eastern emperors to pay tribute.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] An additional problem to face the empire came as a result of the involvement of Emperor Maurice (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 582–602) in Persian politics when he intervened in a succession dispute.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] This led to a period of peace, but when Maurice was overthrown, the Persians invaded and during the reign of Emperor Heraclius (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 610–641) controlled large chunks of the empire, including Egypt, Syria, and Anatolia until Heraclius' successful counterattack.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 628, the empire secured a peace treaty and recovered its lost territories.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In Western Europe, some older Roman elite families died out while others became more involved with ecclesiastical than secular affairs.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Values attached to Latin scholarship and education mostly disappeared, and while literacy remained important, it became a practical skill rather than a sign of elite status.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 420) dreamed that God rebuked him for spending more time reading Cicero than the Bible.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the 6th century, Gregory of Tours (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 594) had a similar dream, but instead of being chastised for reading Cicero, he was chastised for learning shorthand.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the late 6th century, the principal means of religious instruction in the Church had become music and art rather than the book.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Most intellectual efforts went towards imitating classical scholarship, but some original works were created, along with now-lost oral compositions.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The writings of Sidonius Apollinaris (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Changes also occurred among laypeople, as aristocratic culture focused on great feasts held in halls rather than on literary pursuits.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Clothing for the elites was richly embellished with jewels and gold.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Lords and kings supported the entourages of fighters who formed the backbone of the military forces.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Family ties within the elites were important, as were the virtues of loyalty, courage, and honour.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] These ties led to the prevalence of feuds in aristocratic society, including those related by Gregory of Tours in Merovingian Gaul.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Most feuds seem to have ended quickly with the payment of some compensation.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Women took part in aristocratic society mainly in their roles as wives and mothers of men, with the role of mother of a ruler being especially prominent in Merovingian Gaul.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In Anglo-Saxon society, the lack of many child rulers meant a lesser role for women as queen mothers, but this was compensated for by the increased role played by abbesses of monasteries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Only in Italy does it appear that women were always considered under the protection and control of a male relative.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Peasant society is much less documented than the nobility.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Most of the surviving information available to historians comes from archaeology; few detailed written records documenting peasant life remain from before the 9th century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Most of the descriptions of the lower classes come from either law codes or writers from the upper classes.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Landholding patterns in the West were not uniform; some areas had greatly fragmented landholding patterns, but in other areas, large contiguous blocks of land were the norm.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] These differences allowed for a wide variety of peasant societies, some dominated by aristocratic landholders and others having great autonomy.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Some peasants lived in large settlements that numbered as many as 700 inhabitants.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Others lived in small groups of a few families and lived on isolated farms spread over the countryside.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] There were also areas where the pattern was a mix of two or more systems.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Unlike in the late Roman period, there was no sharp break between the legal status of the free peasant and the aristocrat, and a free peasant's family could rise into the aristocracy over several generations through military service to a powerful lord.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Roman city life and culture changed greatly in the early Middle Ages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Although Italian cities remained inhabited, they contracted significantly in size.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] For instance, Rome shrank from hundreds of thousands to around 30,000 by the end of the 6th century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Roman temples were converted into Christian churches and city walls remained in use.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In Northern Europe, cities also shrank, while civic monuments and other public buildings were raided for building materials.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The establishment of new kingdoms often meant some growth for the towns chosen as capitals.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Although there had been Jewish communities in many Roman cities, the Jews suffered periods of persecution after the conversion of the empire to Christianity.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Officially, they were tolerated, if subject to conversion efforts, and were sometimes encouraged to settle in new areas.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Religious beliefs in the Eastern Roman Empire and Iran were in flux during the late sixth and early seventh centuries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Judaism was an active proselytising faith, and at least one Arab political leader converted to it.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In addition Jewish theologians wrote polemics defending their religion against Christian and Islamic influences.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Christianity had active missions competing with the Persians' Zoroastrianism in seeking converts, especially among residents of the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] All these strands came together with the emergence of Islam in Arabia during the lifetime of Muhammad (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] After his death, Islamic forces conquered much of the Eastern Roman Empire and Persia, starting with Syria in 634–635, continuing with Persia between 637 and 642, reaching Egypt in 640–641, North Africa in the later seventh century, and the Iberian Peninsula in 711.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By 714, Islamic forces controlled much of the peninsula in a region they called Al-Andalus.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Islamic conquests reached their peak in the mid-eighth century.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The defeat of Muslim forces at the Battle of Tours in 732 led to the reconquest of southern France by the Franks, but the main reason for the halt of Islamic growth in Europe was the overthrow of the Umayyad Caliphate and its replacement by the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Abbasids moved their capital to Baghdad and were more concerned with the Middle East than Europe, losing control of sections of the Muslim lands.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Umayyad descendants took over the Iberian Peninsula, the Aghlabids controlled North Africa, and the Tulunids became rulers of Egypt.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the middle of the 8th century, new trading patterns were emerging in the Mediterranean; trade between the Franks and the Arabs replaced the old Roman economy.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Franks traded timber, furs, swords, and enslaved people in return for silks and other fabrics, spices, and precious metals from the Arabs.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The migrations and invasions of the 4th and 5th centuries disrupted trade networks around the Mediterranean.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] African goods stopped being imported into Europe, first disappearing from the interior and, by the 7th century, found only in a few cities such as Rome or Naples.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the end of the 7th century, under the impact of the Muslim conquests, African products were no longer found in Western Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Replacing goods from long-range trade with local products was a trend throughout the old Roman lands in the Early Middle Ages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] This was especially marked in the lands that did not lie on the Mediterranean, such as northern Gaul or Britain.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Non-local goods appearing in the archaeological record are usually luxury goods.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In northern Europe, not only were the trade networks local, but the goods carried were simple, with little pottery or other complex products.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Around the Mediterranean, pottery remained prevalent and appears to have been traded over medium-range networks, not just produced locally.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The various Germanic states in the west all had coinages that imitated existing Roman and Byzantine forms.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Gold continued to be minted until the end of the 7th century in 693–694, when it was replaced by silver in the Merovingian kingdom.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The basic Frankish silver coin was the denarius or denier, while the Anglo-Saxon version was called a penny.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] From these areas, the denier or penny spread throughout Europe from 700 to 1000.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Copper or bronze coins were not struck, nor were gold, except in Southern Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] No silver coins denominated in multiple units were minted.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Christianity was a major unifying factor between Eastern and Western Europe before the Arab conquests, but the conquest of North Africa sundered maritime connections between those areas.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Increasingly, the Byzantine Church differed in language, practices, and liturgy from the Western Church.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Eastern Church used Greek instead of Western Latin.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Theological and political differences emerged, and by the early and middle 8th century, issues such as iconoclasm, clerical marriage, and state control of the Church had widened to the extent that the cultural and religious differences were more significant than the similarities.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The ecclesiastical structure of the Roman Empire survived the movements and invasions in the West mostly intact.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Still, the papacy was little regarded, and few of the Western bishops looked to the bishop of Rome for religious or political leadership.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Many of the popes before 750 were more concerned with Byzantine affairs and Eastern theological controversies.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The register, or archived copies of the letters, of Pope Gregory the Great (pope 590–604) survived.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Of those 850 letters, most were concerned with affairs in Italy or Constantinople.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The only part of Western Europe where the papacy had influence was Britain, where Gregory had sent the Gregorian mission in 597 to convert the Anglo-Saxons to Christianity.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Irish missionaries were most active in Western Europe between the 5th and the 7th centuries, going first to England and Scotland and then on to the continent.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 615), they founded monasteries, taught in Latin and Greek, and authored secular and religious works.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Early Middle Ages witnessed the rise of monasticism in the West.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The shape of European monasticism was determined by traditions and ideas that originated with the Desert Fathers of Egypt and Syria.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Most European monasteries were of the type that focuses on the community experience of the spiritual life, called cenobitism, which was pioneered by Pachomius (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Monastic ideals spread from Egypt to Western Europe in the 5th and 6th centuries through hagiographical literature such as the *Life of Anthony*.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 547) wrote the Benedictine Rule for Western monasticism during the 6th century, detailing the administrative and spiritual responsibilities of a community of monks led by an abbot.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Monks and monasteries had a profound effect on the religious and political life of the Early Middle Ages, in various cases acting as land trusts for powerful families, centres of propaganda and royal support in newly conquered regions, and bases for missions and proselytisation.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] They were the main and sometimes only outposts of education and literacy in a region.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Many of the surviving manuscripts of the Latin classics were copied in monasteries in the Early Middle Ages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Monks were also the authors of new works, including history, theology, and other subjects, written by authors such as Bede (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 735), a native of northern England who wrote in the late 7th and early 8th centuries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Frankish kingdom in northern Gaul split into kingdoms called Austrasia, Neustria, and Burgundy during the 6th and 7th centuries, all of them ruled by the Merovingian dynasty, who were descended from Clovis.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The 7th century was a tumultuous period of wars between Austrasia and Neustria.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Such warfare was exploited by Pippin I (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 640), the Mayor of the Palace for Austrasia who became the power behind the Austrasian throne.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Later, his family inherited the office and acted as advisers and regents.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] One of his descendants, Charles Martel (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 741), won the Battle of Poitiers in 732, halting the advance of Muslim armies across the Pyrenees.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Great Britain was divided into small states dominated by the kingdoms of Northumbria, Mercia, Wessex, and East Anglia which descended from the Anglo-Saxon invaders.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Smaller kingdoms in present-day Wales and Scotland were still under the control of the native Britons and Picts.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Ireland was divided into even smaller political units, usually known as tribal kingdoms, under the control of kings.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] There were perhaps as many as 150 local kings in Ireland of varying importance.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Carolingian dynasty, as the successors to Charles Martel are known, officially took control of the kingdoms of Austrasia and Neustria in a coup of 753 led by Pippin III (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] A contemporary chronicle claims that Pippin sought and gained authority for this coup from Pope Stephen II (pope 752–757).
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Pippin's takeover was reinforced with propaganda that portrayed the Merovingians as inept or cruel rulers, exalted the accomplishments of Charles Martel, and circulated stories of the family's great piety.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] At the time of his death in 768, Pippin left his kingdom in the hands of his two sons, Charles (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] When Carloman died of natural causes, Charles blocked the succession of Carloman's young son and installed himself as the king of the united Austrasia and Neustria.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charles, more often known as Charles the Great or Charlemagne, embarked upon a programme of systematic expansion in 774 that unified a large portion of Europe, eventually controlling modern-day France, northern Italy, and Saxony.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the wars that lasted beyond 800, he rewarded allies with war booty and command over parcels of land.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 774, Charlemagne conquered the Lombards, which freed the papacy from the fear of Lombard conquest and marked the beginnings of the Papal States.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The coronation of Charlemagne as emperor on Christmas Day 800 is regarded as a turning point in medieval history, marking a return of the Western Roman Empire since the new emperor ruled over much of the area previously controlled by the Western emperors.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] It also marks a change in Charlemagne's relationship with the Byzantine Empire, as the assumption of the imperial title by the Carolingians asserted their equivalence to the Byzantine state.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] There were several differences between the newly established Carolingian Empire and both the older Western Roman Empire and the concurrent Byzantine Empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Frankish lands were rural, with only a few small cities.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Most of the people were peasants who settled on small farms.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Little trade existed, and much of that was with the British Isles and Scandinavia, in contrast to the older Roman Empire with its trading networks centred on the Mediterranean.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The empire was administered by an itinerant court that travelled with the emperor, as well as approximately 300 imperial officials called counts, who administered the counties the empire had been divided into.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Clergy and local bishops served as officials, as well as the imperial officials, called *missi dominici*, who served as roving inspectors and troubleshooters.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charlemagne's court in Aachen was the centre of the cultural revival, sometimes referred to as the "Carolingian Renaissance".
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Literacy increased, as did development in the arts, architecture, jurisprudence, and liturgical and scriptural studies.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 804) was invited to Aachen and brought the education available in the monasteries of Northumbria.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charlemagne's chancery—or writing office—made use of a new script today known as Carolingian minuscule, allowing a standard writing style that advanced communication across much of Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charlemagne sponsored changes in church liturgy, imposing the Roman form of church service on his domains, as well as the Gregorian chant in liturgical music for the churches.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] An important activity for scholars during this period was copying, correcting, and disseminating basic works on religious and secular topics to encourage learning.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] New works on religious topics and schoolbooks were also produced.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Grammarians of the period modified the Latin language, changing it from the Classical Latin of the Roman Empire into a more flexible form to fit the needs of the Church and government.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the reign of Charlemagne, the language had so diverged from the classical Latin that it was later called Medieval Latin.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charlemagne planned to continue the Frankish tradition of dividing his kingdom between all his heirs but was unable to do so as only one son, Louis the Pious (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Just before Charlemagne died in 814, he crowned Louis as his successor.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Numerous divisions of the empire marked Louis's reign of 26 years among his sons and, after 829, civil wars between various alliances of father and sons over the control of various parts of the empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Eventually, Louis recognised his eldest son Lothair I (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Louis divided the rest of the empire between Lothair and Charles the Bald (d.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Lothair took East Francia, comprising both banks of the Rhine and eastwards, leaving Charles West Francia with the empire to the west of the Rhineland and the Alps.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 876), the middle child, who had been rebellious to the last, was allowed to keep Bavaria under the suzerainty of his elder brother.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Pepin II of Aquitaine (d. after 864), the emperor's grandson, rebelled in a contest for Aquitaine, while Louis the German tried to annexe all of East Francia.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Louis the Pious died in 840, with the empire still in chaos.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] A three-year civil war followed his death.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the Treaty of Verdun (843), a kingdom between the Rhine and Rhone rivers was created for Lothair to go with his lands in Italy, and his imperial title was recognised.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Louis the German controlled Bavaria and the eastern lands in modern-day Germany.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charles the Bald received the western Frankish lands, comprising most of modern-day France.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charlemagne's grandsons and great-grandsons divided their kingdoms between their descendants, eventually causing all internal cohesion to be lost.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 987, the Carolingian dynasty was replaced in the western lands, with the crowning of Hugh Capet (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the eastern lands, the dynasty had died out earlier, in 911, with the death of Louis the Child, and the selection of the unrelated Conrad I (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Invasions, migrations, and raids by external foes accompanied the break-up of the Carolingian Empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The Atlantic and northern shores were harassed by the Vikings, who also raided the British Isles and settled there and in Iceland.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 911, the Viking chieftain Rollo (d. c.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 931) received permission from the Frankish King Charles the Simple (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 898–922) to settle in what became Normandy.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The eastern parts of the Frankish kingdoms, especially Germany and Italy, were under continual Magyar assault until the invader's defeat at the Battle of Lechfeld in 955.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The break-up of the Abbasid dynasty meant that the Islamic world fragmented into smaller political states, some of which began expanding into Italy and Sicily, as well as over the Pyrenees into the southern parts of the Frankish kingdoms.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Efforts by local kings to fight the invaders led to the formation of new political entities.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In Anglo-Saxon England, King Alfred the Great (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 871–899) came to an agreement with the Viking invaders in the late 9th century, resulting in Danish settlements in Northumbria, Mercia, and parts of East Anglia.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the middle of the 10th century, Alfred's successors had conquered Northumbria and restored English control over most of the southern part of Great Britain.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In northern Britain, Kenneth MacAlpin (d. c.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 860) united the Picts and the Scots into the Kingdom of Alba.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In the early 10th century, the Ottonian dynasty had established itself in Germany, and was engaged in driving back the Magyars.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Its efforts culminated in the coronation in 962 of Otto I (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In 972, he secured recognition of his title by the Byzantine Empire, which he sealed with the marriage of his son Otto II (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 991), daughter of an earlier Byzantine Emperor Romanos II (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the late 10th century Italy had been drawn into the Ottonian sphere after a period of instability; Otto III (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 996–1002) spent much of his later reign there.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The western Frankish kingdom was more fragmented, and although kings remained nominally in charge, much of the political power devolved to the local lords.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Missionary efforts to Scandinavia during the 9th and 10th centuries helped strengthen the growth of kingdoms such as Sweden, Denmark, and Norway, which gained power and territory.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Some kings converted to Christianity, although by the year 1000, not all had done so.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Scandinavians also expanded and colonised throughout Europe.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Besides the settlements in Ireland, England, and Normandy, further settlement took place in what became Russia and Iceland.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Swedish traders and raiders ranged down the rivers of the Russian steppe and even attempted to seize Constantinople in 860 and 907.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Christian Spain, initially driven into a small section of the peninsula in the north, expanded slowly south during the 9th and 10th centuries, establishing the kingdoms of Asturias and León.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In Eastern Europe, Byzantium revived its fortunes under Emperor Basil I (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 913–959), members of the Macedonian dynasty.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Commerce revived, and the emperors oversaw the extension of a uniform administration to all the provinces.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The military was reorganised, which allowed the emperors John I (r.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] 976–1025) to expand the frontiers of the empire on all fronts.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The imperial court was the centre of a revival of classical learning, a process known as the Macedonian Renaissance.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Writers such as John Geometres (fl. early 10th century) composed new hymns, poems, and other works.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Missionary efforts by both Eastern and Western clergy resulted in the conversion of the Moravians, Bulgars, Bohemians, Poles, Magyars, and Slavic inhabitants of the Kievan Rus'.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] These conversions contributed to the founding of political states in the lands of those peoples—the states of Moravia, Bulgaria, Bohemia, Poland, Hungary, and the Kievan Rus'.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Bulgaria, which was founded around 680, at its height reached from Budapest to the Black Sea and from the Dnieper River in modern Ukraine to the Adriatic Sea.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By 1018, the last Bulgarian nobles had surrendered to the Byzantine Empire.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Few large stone buildings were constructed between the Constantinian basilicas of the 4th and 8th centuries, although many smaller ones were built during the 6th and 7th centuries.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] By the beginning of the 8th century, the Carolingian Empire revived the basilica form of architecture.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] One feature of the basilica is the use of a transept, or the "arms" of a cross-shaped building that are perpendicular to the long nave.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Other new features of religious architecture include the crossing tower and a monumental entrance to the church, usually at the west end of the building.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Carolingian art was produced for a small group of figures around the court and the monasteries and churches they supported.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] It was dominated by efforts to regain the dignity and classicism of imperial Roman and Byzantine art but was also influenced by the Insular art of the British Isles.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Insular art integrated the energy of Irish Celtic and Anglo-Saxon Germanic styles of ornament with Mediterranean forms such as the book, and established many characteristics of art for the rest of the medieval period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Surviving religious works from the Early Middle Ages are mostly illuminated manuscripts and carved ivories, originally made for metalwork that has since been melted down.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] There are survivals from the large brooches in fibula or penannular form that were key pieces of personal adornment for elites, including the Irish Tara Brooch.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Highly decorated books were mostly Gospel Books and these have survived in larger numbers, including the Insular Book of Kells, the Book of Lindisfarne, and the imperial Codex Aureus of St.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Emmeram, which is one of the few to retain its "treasure binding" of gold encrusted with jewels.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Charlemagne's court seems to have been responsible for the acceptance of figurative monumental sculpture in Christian art, and by the end of the period near life-sized figures such as the Gero Cross were common in important churches.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] During the later Roman Empire, the principal military developments were attempts to create an effective cavalry force and the continued development of highly specialised types of troops.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The creation of heavily armoured cataphract-type soldiers as cavalry was an important feature of the 5th-century Roman military.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The various invading tribes had differing emphases on types of soldiers—ranging from the primarily infantry centered Anglo-Saxons to the Vandals and Visigoths, who had a high proportion of cavalry in their armies.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] During the early invasion period, the stirrup had not been introduced into warfare, which limited the usefulness of cavalry as shock troops because it was not possible to put the full force of the horse and rider behind blows struck by the rider.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The greatest change in military affairs during the invasion period was the adoption of the Hunnic composite bow in place of the earlier, and weaker, Scythian composite bow.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Another development was the increasing use of longswords and the progressive replacement of scale armour by mail armour and lamellar armour.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The importance of infantry and light cavalry declined during the early Carolingian period, with a growing dominance of elite heavy cavalry.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] The use of militia-type levies of the free population declined over the Carolingian period.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Although much of the Carolingian armies were mounted, a large proportion during the early period appear to have been mounted infantry, rather than true cavalry.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] One exception was Anglo-Saxon England, where the armies were still composed of regional levies, known as the *fyrd*, which were led by the local elites.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] In military technology, one of the main changes was the return of the crossbow, which had been known in Roman times and reappeared as a military weapon during the last part of the Early Middle Ages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] Another change was the introduction of the stirrup, which increased the effectiveness of cavalry as shock troops.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p01] A technological advance that had implications beyond the military was the horseshoe, which allowed horses to be used in rocky terrain.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] The High Middle Ages was a period of tremendous population expansion.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] The estimated population of Europe grew from 35 to 80 million between 1000 and 1347, although the exact causes remain unclear: improved agricultural techniques, the decline of slaveholding, a more clement climate and the lack of invasion have all been suggested.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] As much as 90 per cent of the European population remained rural peasants.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] Many were no longer settled in isolated farms but had gathered into small communities, usually known as manors or villages.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] These peasants were often subject to noble overlords and owed them rents and other services in a system known as manorialism.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] There remained a few free peasants throughout this period and beyond, with more of them in the regions of Southern Europe than in the north.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] The practice of assarting, or bringing new lands into production by offering incentives to the peasants who settled them, also contributed to population expansion.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] The open-field system of agriculture was commonly practised in most of Europe, especially in "northwestern and central Europe".
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] Some regions used a three-field system of crop rotation; others retained the older two-field system.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] Other sections of society included the nobility, clergy, and townspeople.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] Nobles, both the titled nobility and simple knights, exploited the manors and the peasants.
[src:middle-ages/middle-ages-p02] However, they did not own lands outright but were granted rights to the income from a manor or other lands by an overlord through the system of feudalism.
